<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Retail Sales Decline for Third Straight Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Retail sales in the U.S.
declined by 0.1 percent in May, the third straight drop, the U.S.
Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that U.S. retail sales slipped another 0.1
percent last month following declines of 0.9 percent in April and
0.3 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
The three straight declines in the retail sales were the first
since consecutive drops in September through November of 1981, at
the end of the severe 1980-81 recession.
</P>
<P>
The drop of retail sales were led by a 0.2 percent decline in
auto sales, the third straight decrease. Auto demand had slumped a
sharp 2 percent in April and was down 1.2 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
The nation's largest department stores also reported weak sales
for May compared with the same month a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The setbacks in retail spending, which account for one-third of
total U.S. economic activity, are the clearest signal so far that
the U.S. economy has slowed from its 5.8 percent growth rate in
the first three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
The prospect of moderating growth that will keep inflation
under control has been a key factor behind the recent surge in the
stock market. Investors are growing more confident that the U.S.
Federal Reserve (Fed) will not increase interest rates when its
policy-makers meet July 1-2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
