<HEADLINE> S.Africa Improves World Rating in UNDP Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has been ranked
90th, compared to 100th last year, out of 175 countries worldwide
in achievements of life expectancy, educational attainment and
adjusted real income, according to the United Nations Human
Development Report for 1997 released in Cape Town today.
</P>
<P>
South Africa improved its score this year maily to revision of
the data for life expectancy and real gross domestic product
(GDP) per capita, said the report, which also includes the human
development index (HDI).
</P>
<P>
However, the report pointed out that the progress in South
Africa's fight against human poverty remains uneven, and stark
disparities still exist between different race groups.
</P>
<P>
In South Africa, the per capita income of the richest 20
percent was 19 times that of the poorest 20 percent, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
The real per capita GDP of the richest 20 percent stood at
9897 US Dollars while that of the poorest 20 percent was 516 US
Dollar.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South Africa's HDI rank of 90 was still below its
ranking of 80th with regard to real per capita GDP in terms of
purchasing power parity.
</P>
<P>
Statistics in the report further showed that 17 percent of
South Africans were not expected to survive until the age of 40,
among which only three percent of the Whites and 18 percent of
the Blacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
