<HEADLINE> Kesri Re-elected President of Congress Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Sitaram Kesri, the incumbent
president of India's Congress Party, has been re-elected according
to the results of the elections held on June 9, Press Trust of
India reported today.
</P>
<P>
The 81-year-old Kesri retained the post after defeating another
two senior Congress party leaders Sharad Pawar and Rajesh Pilot in
the poll.
</P>
<P>
The counting of the votes began this morning only after all the
ballot boxes were collected and brought to the party headquarters
in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Over 8,000 party delegates, mainly party leaders at different
levels, voted in the June 9 exercise which was held after the
party failed to find a consensus candidate on the post.
</P>
<P>
Kesri became provisional party president in September last year
when his predecessor P.V. Narasimha Rao was forced to step down
due to his alleged involvement in a scandal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
