<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Asian-American to Be Named to Top Civil Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- An Asian-American lawyer in Los
Angeles will be named to the government's top civil rights post,
media reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton will appoint Bill Lann Lee, 48, as
assistant attorney general for civil rights, making him the first
person other than a white or black to hold the job.
</P>
<P>
If confirmed by the Senate, Lee, the son of Chinese immigrants,
would fill a position that has been vacant since the resignation
of Deval Patrick seven months ago. The division is charged with
litigating discrimination cases in housing, employment, education
and public accommodations.
</P>
<P>
Lee's father was penniless when he arrived as an immigrant in
New York City, but managed to establish Lee's Hand Laundry on the
outskirts of Harlem, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
With the help of a scholarship, Lee graduated Phi Betta Kappa
from Yale and later attended Columbia University Law School. He
has worked for the NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund Inc.
for 24 years, and currently directs its western regional office.
</P>
</TEXT>
