<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Budget Placed in Bangladeshi Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Finance Minister Shah
A.M.S. Kibria today placed in parliament 277.85 billion taka
(about 6.46 billion U.S. dollars) proposed national budget for the
1997-98 fiscal year from this July to next June.
</P>
<P>
The new budget, which includes a development outlay worth 128
billion taka (about 2.98 billion dollars) and food-for-works and
non-development project allocation of 4.4 billion taka (about 102
million dollars), set the economy growth rate as 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Although this was the second budget of the year-long government
of Sheikh Hasina, the new budget was considered as the first one
of its own because the last budget was made on the estimates of
the caretaker administration.
</P>
<P>
The budget estimated a revenue receipt of 196.24 billion taka
(about 4.56 billion dollars) and revenue expenditure of some
145.44 billion taka (about 3.38 billion dollars), leaving a
revenue surplus of 50.8 billion taka (about 1.18 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The revenue surplus will go to finance the Annual Development
Program (ADP), the government's development budget, which is 11
billion taka (about 256 million dollars) more than the revised ADP
of 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
The ADP, with 54 percent of the fund coming from the domestic
resources, is to raise growth of gross domestic product (GDP) to
at least 6 percent from the current 5.7 percent, said the finance
minister.
</P>
<P>
He said the tax proposals for the year 1997-98 had been
formulated keeping in mind introduction of a broad-base tax
system, in which the existing tax exemptions would be gradually
eliminated and every well-to-do person in the country would be
brought under the tax-net.
</P>
<P>
The budget proposals also introduced moderate tax rate and
simple collection procedures, while a tariff policy in line with
the international and regional trends has been proposed, said the
finance minister, adding that the progressive tax policy can
ensure social justice and equity.
</P>
<P>
Economic analysts here said that the key aspect of the next
fiscal budget would be the implementation of the new pay scale for
government officials.
</P>
<P>
It has been estimated that an additional amount of 16 billion
taka (about 372 million dollars) would be required to implement
the new scales. To meet the gap, the government will have to
borrow from the banking sector, which was described by the central
bank governor as being "on the verge of collapse".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
