<HEADLINE> Sassou N'Guesso Threatens to Stop French Planes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Former president of the Congo
Republic General Sassou N'Guesso today threatened to stop French
planes from landing at the Brazzaville airport, if French troops
do not prevent his rival, President Pascal Lissouba, from using
the airport to receive reinforcements.
</P>
<P>
Sassou N'Guesso made the threat at an impromptu meeting with a
superior French officer stationed in Brazzaville, according to
Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
"We cannot accept that Lissouba use (airport) to transport
troops and ammunitions... We are at the end of the runway. If
necessary, we will ban all landing (of planes)," said Sassou
N'Guesso.
</P>
<P>
France has ruled out the possibility of intervening in the
fighting between the forces of Sassou N'Guesso and Lissouba, and
said that the 1,250 French troops deployed in Congo would leave as
soon as they have completed evacuating foreigners stranded in
Congo.
</P>
<P>
French troops have been using the Brazzaville airport to
evacuate thousands of foreigners from Brazzaville over the past
several days.
</P>
<P>
One French soldier was wounded today on the runway of the
airport, bringing the casualties inflicted upon the French troops
to one dead and seven wounded, two of them seriously, reported
AFP.
</P>
<P>
The leg of the French soldier was hit by a bullet in an
exchange of fires between Congolese government troops and the
"Cobra" militiamen of Sassou-N'Guesso.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, mortar shellings and shootings of automatic weapons
resumed this afternoon in Brazzaville between the government
forces and the Cobra militiamen along the "Peace Avenue"
approximately diving the northern and southern parts of the city
controlled separately by the two sides, according to reports
reaching here.
</P>
<P>
French troops were using armored vehicles to look for
foreigners stranded in dangerous areas and escort them to the
airport. 
</P>
</TEXT>
