<HEADLINE> World Bank Aims to Halve World Poor by 2015 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank aims to cut in half
the figure of the poor people in the world by 2015, World Bank
President James Wolfensohn told reporters here today.
</P>
<P>
Three billion people live with less than two U.S. dollars a day
and 1.3 billion on less than one U.S. dollars a day, Wolfensohn
said, pledging that the World Bank aims at "halving the figure of
poor people by 2015". Wolfensohn said that "Our world is a world
of great differences between countries: the rich and the poor, a
world of great inequities within countries, between the rich and
the poor, and those inequities are increasing".
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn is not satisfied with the investment flows of the
private sector. Of 240 billion U.S. dollars from the private
sector, he said, 75 percent goes to 12 countries or regions. 140
countries get less than five percent and Sub-Saharan Africa gets
around one percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
