<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Critised at CITES Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Japan appeared today to be on a
collision course with animal rights groups which are accusing the
economic giant of bribing weaker third world countries to buy
support for its marine policies.
</P>
<P>
The International Fund for Animal Welfare (IFAW) said in a
report at the ongoing 10th conference of the Convention on
International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES) in Harare that
Japan was now applying its strategy on other wildlife issues such
as the ivory trade to support its agenda.
</P>
<P>
Lesley Sutty, author of the report co-sponsored by the Eastern
Caribbean Coalition for Environmental Awareness (ECCEA), told a
press briefing that Japan had systematically targeted countries
in the south Pacific, Latin America and Africa, offering
multi-million dollar grants and soft loans.
</P>
<P>
She said having seen its technique succeed in staving off
anti-whaling measures in the 1980s and early 1990s, Japan had now
extended it to elephants, a species considered in danger of
extinction by CITES.
</P>
<P>
She said Japan, with a potentially huge and lucrative market
for ivory, was supporting the downlisting of the elephant from
the CITES appendix i to appendix ii.
</P>
<P>
Greenpeace, a leading environmental group today said Japan,
which is willing to buy Africa's ivory, does not have adequate
measures to control illegal trade.
</P>
<P>
The organisation held that in the event of a partial
relaxation of the international trade ban on ivory and other
elephant products, poaching is likely to restart. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's Violent Crimes Up in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Germany's violent crime rose by 5.5
percent to 180,000 cases, about 219 per 100,000 persons, in
Germany in 1996, but homicides declined slightly.
</P>
<P>
A report released today by German Interior Minister Manfred
Kanther said the number of crimes committed by armed offenders
last year rose to 13,479 cases, up from 12,855 over the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
Last year also saw rape cases in the country increase to 6,228,
from 6,175 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Crimes by youths under 14 years old grew more than 12 percent
to over 131,000 cases in the year, while crimes by young people
aged 14-18 jumped by nine percent to 277,479 cases.
</P>
<P>
There were 1,224 registered cases of murder or manslaughter in
Germany last year, 1.5 cases per 100,000 people, representing a
decline from 1,343 cases (1.6 cases per 100,000) in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
