<HEADLINE> Harare Residents' Health Deteriorating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Harare city council today said
the health status of the capital, which has a population of more
than 1.4 million, continues to deteriorate as infant mortality
rose by 11 percent during the past year.
</P>
<P>
According to its annual report for 1996, the falling health
standards in the capital were attributed to increasing poverty,
overcrowding and malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
City health director Lovemore Mbengeranwa said in the report
the rapid urbanisation was causing an increase in poverty-related
deaths, diseases associoted with industrialisation and social
instability.
</P>
<P>
"The city's health status continues to deteriorate as
evidenced by the rising infant mortality and the mortality of
those under the age of five years," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the problem of HIV/AIDS epidemic is also an
important factor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
