<HEADLINE> World Bank Pledges Strengthened Relations with ILO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The cooperative relations between
the World Bank and the International Labor Organization (ILO)
should be deepened, World Bank President James Wolfensohn said
here today in a speech at the ongoing 85th International Labor
Conference.
</P>
<P>
"We have to get away from theoretical exercises, from mutual
expressions of goodwill, to targets, to evaluations, to focusing
on projects on which we can work together," he added.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn claimed that the goals of the ILO and those of the
World Bank are "absolutely linked," although the ways in which
they work are different.
</P>
<P>
President of the Conference and Slovak's Labor Minister, Olga
Keltosova, said she is "confident that the World Bank is now an
important partner" in promoting social justice.
</P>
<P>
"We are convinced that cooperation between the World Bank and
the ILO will be beneficial to all of our constituents," she said.
</P>
