<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Pak New Budget to Be Unveiled amid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The government led by Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif, which came to power in mid February, is to
present its first budget Friday amid mixed expectations and in the
backdrop of chronic economic problems.
</P>
<P>
With the national budget for the 1997-98 fiscal year to be
unfolded by Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz, the government is
confronted with an uphill task of reviving an almost collapsed
economy.
</P>
<P>
Despite unprecedented perils looming over Pakistan's economic
frontiers, the government seems quite determined to execute
massive surgery of the economy which is already on through drastic
economic measures.
</P>
<P>
Extensive economic agenda pursued by the government for the
resurgence of the crisis-strapped economy still needs a lot to be
done for the consumers, who are facing acute problems of price
hikes and eroding purchasing power.
</P>
<P>
The current fiscal year will be remembered as the worst in
Pakistan's economic history, which is experiencing a rapid
deterioration of macroeconomic management.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's economy used to grow at a healthy rate of around
seven percent on average, yet it saw a major breakdown in its pace
in the 1996-97 fiscal year with estimates indicating its
deceleration to 3.1 percent by the end of June 30.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural sector, which accounts for a quarter of Gross
Domestic Product (GDP), is assessed to record a near negative
growth and the large-scale manufacturing sector, 1.4 percent in
the out-going fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The fiscal deficit, targeted to be four percent of the GDP, is
in no way near the target.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's total national debt has reached a staggering 60
billion US dollars and is expected to eat away almost two-thirds
of the federal tax receipts in the next fiscal year only in terms
of its servicing.
</P>
<P>
The low rates of investment stagnated at 18 to 20 percent of
GDP, and poor domestic saving rate, fluctuating between 10-15
percent, is very low by the standards in comparable countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, with exports falling well short of targeted 10
billion dollars and imports crossing 12 billion dollar mark, the
trade deficit is expected to reach 3.2 billion dollars by the end
of the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Economists here believe that in this serious situation, the
budget for the next fiscal year will be very tough.
</P>
<P>
The present government of the Pakistan Muslim League (PML) came
to power on February 17, with just the last quarter to go before
the end of the current fiscal year. The new government had to
react promptly to at least arrest further economic decay.
</P>
<P>
The PML government has put forward seven economic reform
packages, primarily aiming to boost exports, reform the banking
system, revive industrial growth and augment capital market to put
the economy back on track.
</P>
<P>
To ease the ever growing debt burden, the government has also
approved a program for privatization of all state-owned
enterprises. It is widely considered as a prime tool to get rid of
the debt burden which has long been a major cause for lower
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the present government has been making great efforts
in reforming the banking sector, most noticeably by granting the
autonomous status to the State Bank of Pakistan (SBP), the
controlling institution of the entire banking network.
</P>
<P>
Through an amendment to the State Bank of Pakistan Act 1956,
the SBP has been given full autonomy in administrative matters. It
has been empowered to decide the limits of the bank borrowing by
the federal and provincial governments from commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
Because of the revenue shortfall and the burgeoning budget
deficit, the government's borrowing from commercial banks during
the past few years has been increasing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
The government's bank borrowing in the current fiscal year
alone is expected to reach about 100 billion rupees (about 2.4
billion dollars) as against the revised budget ceiling barrier of
44 billion (1.07 billion dollars) the whole fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
It had led not only to the rising budget deficit but made the
private sector desperately look for working capital, which was
eaten away by the public sector.
</P>
<P>
The budget, to be presented Friday in this dismal backdrop, is
nothing but a serious challenge for the government to turn around
the economy.
</P>
<P>
Debt-servicing and defense expenditure will, as usual, occupy
the top two slots on the expenditure side. In the fiscal 1995-96,
the debt-servicing was 186.1 billion rupees (4.54 billion dollars)
with the defense budget consuming 131.4 billion rupees (3.2
billion dollars) out of the total outlay of 500 billion rupees
(12.2 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The National Economic Council has already approved the proposed
Public Sector Development Program worth 95 billion (2.3 billion
dollars) for the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Aiming to achieve an export target of 10.5 billion dollars, the
government intends to bring down the trade gap to 2 billion
dollars from the current level of more than 3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Cutting down the non-development expenditure and increasing the
revenue are believed to be the only two options for the government
to extricate the economy from the current difficult position.
</P>
<P>
The government has already introduced measures to cut down the
current expenditure, and according to Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz
about 30 billion rupees (703 million dollars) has been saved since
the government came to power in mid February.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Direct Talks Help Cyprus Solution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
formally extended Wednesday invitations to Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash to
attend the U.N.-sponsored direct negotiations on the Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
Annan himself will open the first round of negotiations
scheduled between July 9 and 13 somewhere near New York.
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming event will be the first face-to-face meeting
between Clerides and Denktash since October, 1994 when they held
two rounds of informal talks under the U.N. auspices, which ended
in a deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Both the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides have responded
positively to the invitations. Government Spokesman Manolis
Christofides described the U.N. move as "the beginning of a new
effort" towards a solution to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Denktash said Wednesday that he would go to the talks with good
will and to defend the rights of the Turkish Cypriot community,
adding "We hope it will be a new beginning with a new spirit."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot south and the
Turkish Cypriot north since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded and
took control of the northern third of the island in the wake of a
pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Nine years after the division of the island, the Turkish
Cypriot side established a breakaway state "The Turkish Republic
of Northern Cyprus," which is recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The U.N., keeping a 1,200-strong peacekeeping force in Cyprus,
has been mediating between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides for
a solution for the past 23 years, but no tangible results have
been achieved so far.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.'s fresh peace initiative started from March this
year, when U.N. Chief's Resident Representative in Cyprus Gustave
Feissel conducted the proximity talks between Clerides and
Denktash in an effort to create a right climate for the direct
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Both the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides have shown their
good-will gestures during the talks by announcing the suspension
of the Greek and Turkish military aircraft flying over the Cyprus
air space, thus reducing the tension on the island.
</P>
<P>
However, the prospects of these long-waited direct negotiations
are not so optimistic since differences on main aspects of the
Cyprus problem have remained unsolved between the two sides
despite the U.N.'s shuttle mediations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Direct Talks Help Cyprus Solution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The fundamental issues of the Cyprus problem, such as
sovereignty, political equality, security, territorial adjustment
and free movement, free settlement and respect of property, are
expected to be on the agenda of the direct talks.
</P>
<P>
Among them, Clerides has singled out security as a key issue
whose solution closely links to the fate of the whole Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Cypriot side has been advocating a demilitarization
idea, which deprives both communities of armed protection and
entrusts a proposed international force with security
responsibility instead.
</P>
<P>
The proposal, put forward by Clerides in 1993, also suggests
the abolition of the intervention right of Greece, Turkey and
Britain, the guarantors of Cyprus' independence under the 1960
treaty of establishment of the Cyprus Republic.
</P>
<P>
But it has met rejection by Denktash who insisted on the
maintenance of around 30,000 Turkish troops on the island to
protect the Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has also asked the Greek Cypriot side to respect the
Turkish Cypriots' "rights, equality and sovereignty" -- or to
accept the fact "that we shall only be good neighbors in our own
areas."
</P>
<P>
Speaking after conveying the U.N. Chief's invitations to
Clerides and Denktash, U.N. Resident Representative Gustave
Feissel called for contribution from both sides to an overall
settlement, saying "No settlement is possible if one side or the
other side says this or that is out of bounds."
</P>
<P>
Observers here believed that the forthcoming U.N.-sponsored
direct negotiations will be a step forward in finding a
comprehensive solution to the protracted Cyprus problem, but
expressing an cautious optimism.
</P>
<P>
They echoed statements Wednesday by the newly-appointed U.S.
Presidential Emissary for Cyprus, Richard Holbrooke, that "if
the talks make progress it gives us a little momentum to
build on. If not, at least we will have a clearer picture
where the issues are, so there is no downside to this
meeting." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNSCOM Inspectors Attempt to Smuggle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has formally informed the
U.N. of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) inspectors' attempt
to smuggle articles which are not allowed to be taken out of the
country under Iraqi laws, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported
today.
</P>
<P>
A letter, addressed Wednesday by Iraqi Foreign Minister
Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf to U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan,
said Iraq considers the act as violation of its laws and a
flagrant bid to undermine its national economy, as well as a
premeditated contravention of the international norms.
</P>
<P>
The letter said that Iraqi authorities have obtained
information that on June 5, certain UNSCOM inspectors in Iraq
tried to transport illicitly certain articles, which are not
allowed to be taken out of the country under the laws, out of Iraq
through UNSCOM helicopters at an Iraqi airport. The articles are
allegedly in the trunks belonging to the helicopters' pilots.
</P>
<P>
However, neither the letter nor the INA elaborated what the
articles are.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi authorities concerned have informed Nels Karlstrom,
chief of the UNSCOM Monitoring Center in Baghdad, said the
letter.
</P>
<P>
However, Karlstrom refused to attend a joint examination of
the trunks at the airport.
</P>
<P>
This attempt of smuggling is apparently harmful to Iraq's
national interests, the Iraqi foreign minister concluded,
demanding his letter be circulated as a Security Council
document. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
