<HEADLINE> Taliban Suffers Setback in Eastern Konar Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Islamic Taliban
militia have suffered another setback in two days when opposition
forces today made some territorial gains in eastern Konar
province, Taliban sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban sources in Peshawar, Pakistan's northwestern major
city, said that the Islamic militia lost the Strategic Esmar
valley, which is near Pakistan border and about 200 kilometers
east of Kabul, to the Eastern Shura forces led by some former
government officials there.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban fighters now were retreating to the west to
Asadabad, capital of Kunar province, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Opposition sources also claimed that they have captured three
other districts in Konar province, which has not been confirmed by
independent sources so far.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Islamic Taliban militia were pushed back by
opposing forces led by former military chief Ahmad Masood from
Pul-e-Khomri, capital of northern Baghlan province, where a large
number of Taliban fighters were being trapped.
</P>
<P>
But Taliban sources claimed that it was a "tactic retreat",
adding that the Taliban were preparing a fresh attack on
Pul-e-Khomri, about 150 kilometers north of Kabul.  
</P>
</TEXT>
