<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OECD Predicts Fair Economic Growth in Industrialized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development (OECD) today predicted a 3 percent
average economic growth in 1997 in its 29 industrialized member
countries, the highest in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
But the international organization regretted high public
deficit and high unemployment rate in continental European
countries, notably Germany, France and Italy.
</P>
<P>
In its half-yearly report published today, the OECD said that
the economic growth will drop to 2.7 percent in 1998 in its 29
industrialized member countries.
</P>
<P>
The United States will score a 3.7 percent growth, Germany 2.2
percent, France 2.5 percent and Italy only 1 percent, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
The three European powers will have difficulty cutting their
public deficit to below 3 percent of their gross domestic product
(GDP), the criteria set by the European Union Maastricht treaty to
qualify for the euro, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Their public deficit will stand at 3.2 percent of their GDP by
the end of 1997, it said. This estimation conforms with a
previous one made by the International Monetary Fund in April.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, Italy's public deficit will rise to 3.8 percent of its
GDP, while those of France and Germany will fall to 3 percent and
2.7 percent of their GDP, it said.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Germany, France, Italy, as well as Greece which will
have its public deficit stay at 6 percent by the end of this year,
all other EU countries will cut their public deficit to below 3
percent of their GDP this year, said the OECD report.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment rate stands at an average of 11.2 percent in EU
countries in 1997, compared with 11.3 percent in 1996, and it will
drop to 10.8 percent in 1998, noted OECD.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate in Germany will rise from 10.3 percent in
1996 to 11.1 percent in 1997, France from 12.4 percent to 12.6
percent, and Italy's unemployment rate will stand at 12.1 percent
this year.
</P>
<P>
The OECD calls on Germany, France and Italy to reduce their
banking rates and make their labor market more flexible in order
to stimulate growth and cut unemployment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
