<HEADLINE> German Bundesbank Optimistic About Resolving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 12 (Xinhua) -- German central bank, the Bundesbank,
today said it saw "good prospects" for an agreement with the Bonn
government to resolve their row over revaluing the country's gold
reserves.
</P>
<P>
"On the basis of the negotiating results so far, the central
bank council sees good prospects for a solution," said the
Bundesbank central council said in a statement issued after its
regular meeting in Frankfurt Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, Bundesbank President Hans Tietmeyer
and his deputy, Johann Wilhelm Gaddum, have been asked to continue
the talks with German Finance Minister Theo Waigel in a bid to
negotiate a detailed quick solution to the issue.
</P>
<P>
But the Bundesbank gave no indication of how the negotiations
with the government were proceeding and appeared set to insist on
its opposition to transferring the windfall profits generated from
the gold revaluation to the government this year.
</P>
<P>
The Bonn government has triggered a feud with the Bundesbank
with its plan announced last month to revalue the bank's
traditionally undervalued gold reserves in line with market prices
and to use the windfall to reduce the country's massive debt in
order to help Bonn qualify for the planned single European
currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
The Bundesbank has warned that the government plan would
infringe on the bank's independence, and risk "a loss in trust in
the stability of the future European currency".
</P>
<P>
While not opposed to using the profits from the gold
revaluation to pay off federal debt, the Bundesbank has been
strongly against being ordered to do so this year.
</P>
<P>
As a compromise, Waigel has proposed to use the money in 1998.
But details of the plan are still under negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
