<HEADLINE> UNDP Urges Nations to Close Gender Gap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) today urged nations to commit
themselves to gender equality in order to unleash the energy and
productive capabilities of women around the world.
</P>
<P>
In its Human Development Report 1997 launched today, UNDP noted
that there is much work to be done in this field.
</P>
<P>
In developing countries, illiterate women outnumber men by 60
percent; women earn only three-fourths of what men earn; women
bear a disproportionately large share of chores and child-bearing
responsibilities; they have less access to land, credit and
employment opportunities. In industrialized countries, the
unemployment rate among women is higher than that among men, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
To help nations monitor their progress in closing the gender
gap, recent editions of the report present two measures of the
disparities in opportunities for men and women around the world.
This year's report includes the following findingds:
</P>
<P>
-- the "Gender-related Development Index," or GDI, measures 146
countries' achievements in life expectancy, educational attainment
and income and compares in status of men and women. Canada, Norway
and Sweden rank the top three, followed by Iceland and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
-- no society treats its women as well as its men as GDI values
in every country are lower than values on a "Human Development
Index", which measures people's well-being;
</P>
<P>
-- gender inequality often accompanies "human poverty," which
reflects limited choices and opportunities; and
</P>
<P>
-- some developing countries outperform much richer
industrialized countries in gender equality in economic and
political opportunities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
