<HEADLINE> U.S. Payment Deal Worries UN Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Diplomats and United
Nations officials were less than enthusiastic today about a deal
worked out by the U.S. Clinton administration and the
Republican-controlled Senate for the payment of the American debt
to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, reportedly reached earlier in the week after
long and tough negotiations between the White House and Congress,
calls for large-scale budget and personnel reductions in the world
body.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times reported today that at least some of the
U.S. demands that U.S. lawmakers propose to make on the U.N.
reform are unlikely to be accepted by many member countries.
</P>
<P>
Most of the requirements the Clinton administration has agreed
to are beyond the power of the U.S. Congress or the U.S.
government to impose on the organization, the paper pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The deal would only pay 819 million U.S. dollars in delinquent
dues over the next three years. The U.N. has calculated the U.S.
debt at over 1 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Prominent among these U.S. requirements are reductions of
American assessments to 20 percent form 25 percent of the regular
U.N. budget and to 25 percent from 31 percent for U.N.
peacekeeping operations. The original percentage was set by
international agreement.
</P>
<P>
The author of the agreement was U.S. Republican Senator Jesse
Helms, Chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, and
Joseph Biden, ranking Democratic on the committee.
</P>
<P>
Some U.S. Congressmen have broken ranks with their colleagues
and argued for full payment of U.S. arrears without conditions.
</P>
<P>
"It is time to decide if we want a strong and viable United
Nations that can serve United States interests or a United Nations
that is crippled by insolvency and hobbled by controversy and
uncertainty," Republican Senator Richard Lugar said in a letter to
Trent Lott, the U.S. Senate majority leader. 
</P>
</TEXT>
