<HEADLINE> German Defense Minister Reassures Bonn's Participation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 12 (Xinhua) -- German Defense Minister Volker Ruehe
said here today that Germany would take part as planned in the
Eurofighter project despite financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Rejecting comments made earlier today by Finance Ministry State
Secretary Manfred Overhaus that Germany's defense budgets must be
cut, Ruehe reiterated that he had received pledges from Finance
Minister Theo Waigel on German participation in the
four-European-nation warplane project which also involves Britain,
Italy and Spain.
</P>
<P>
Ruehe said earlier this month that he expected the Bonn
government to decide on the purchase of Eurofighter jets before
Summer recess in July.
</P>
<P>
Bonn is currently under huge pressure to tighten budgets and
qualify for the single European currency, the euro, which is due
to be launched from 1999. There remain doubts over how to pay for
the bill for the costly Eurofighter jets.
</P>
<P>
Britain, Italy and Spain have already approved the project.
London plans to buy 232 Eurofighter jets, Rome 121 and Madrid 87.
The German armed forces intends to buy 180. The total price for
the four-nation project is estimated at over 65 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Waigel has proposed to redirect Germany's state aid for the
European Airbus Industrie aircraft consortium to help fund the
planned 23 billion German mark (13.6 billion U.S. dollar)
Eurofighter purchase by Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
