<HEADLINE> Egypt's President Arrives in Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
arrived today in Libya for a two-day official visit, according to
reports reaching here from Tripoli, capital of Libya.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan news agency quoted an official source as saying
that Mubarak arrived in the northeast city of Tobruk by car, and
immediately held talks with Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi. The
two leaders were later joined by members of the two countries'
delegations.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak is accompanied by a ministerial delegation
comprising Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, Information Minister
Safwat el-Sherif and Finance Minister Mohi Eddin el-Gharib.
</P>
<P>
In an arrival statement, Mubarak said he will exchange views
with Gaddafi on Arab and international issues.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak will attend during his stay the meetings of a joint
Egyptian-Libyan committee, which will be held later in the day in
Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
The joint committee will consider a plan for a free trade zone
between the two countries and a number of other commercial
projects of mutual interest.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's visit to Libya is taking place 24 hours after Libya
has informed the United Nations about the destructive
consequences of the sanctions imposed against it. The issue of
the sanctions is expected to lead the agenda of the talks between
Mubarak and Gaddafi.
</P>
<P>
Libya sent a message to U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan Wednesday to the effect that the harm and damages done on
account of the international sanctions had recently been
calculated at some 23.5 billion U.S. dollars, apart from other human
and moral damages sustained by the Libyan people.
</P>
<P>
Libya has been under U.N. sanctions since 1992 after Gaddafi
refused to hand over two Libyans suspected in the 1988 bombing of
an American airliner over Locherbie, Scotland that killed 270
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
