<HEADLINE> Cohen Defends U.S. Favor for Three Countries for NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- United States Defense Secretary
William Cohen defended on Thursday his government's choice for
only three new members to join NATO in the first group by saying
that this would underscore that there was going to be addiSmaller enlargement, b
ut this move is said to have shocked some
member states, including France, which has pushed for a broader
enlargement.
</P>
<P>
France, together with some southern European NATO states, has
been voicing strong support for membership of Romania and
Slovenia, in an attempt to balance the expansion to the east with
a "southern strategy".
</P>
<P>
At a press conference after the defense ministers' meeting, Mr
Cohen said that the U.S. approach was appropriate given the fact
that NATO's door would remain open and that there would be ample
opportunities to invite additional members.
</P>
<P>
He argued that by limiting the numbers of new members the
problem of cost of enlargement would be diminished.
</P>
<P>
"A limit initial group will underscore that the process is a
deliberate one,...and there is going to be additional rounds," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Secretary added that the first group of countries
to be invited should enjoy strong consensus since this was "such a
momentous decision" for the alliance.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary General told reporters after the meeting that
the final decision had not yet been taken on which countries would
join in the first wave.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the United States was "a very important
country" in the alliance and that its position would have "without
any doubt a weight" on the decision NATO would finally make.
</P>
</TEXT>
