<HEADLINE> UNDP Affirms China's Success in Poverty Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- China has made impressive
reductions in human poverty in the past 45 years, the United
Nations Development Program (UNDP) reported here today.
</P>
<P>
In its just-released Human Development Report 1997, the UN
agency said that between 1949 and 1995 China reduced infant
mortality from 200 per 1,000 live births to 42, and increased life
expectancy at birth from 35 years to 69.
</P>
<P>
"Today almost all children go to school and adult illiteracy,
80 percent in the 1950s, has fallen to 19 percent," the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The report devoted two pages to China's remarkable progress in
poverty-reduction since 1978.
</P>
<P>
In 1978 the government, concerned about rural poverty, carried
out a special investigation that concluded that 260 million people
lived below the poverty line -- a third of the rural population.
Since then Chinese government took measures to attack rural
poverty, including land reform, market orientation, price reform
of farm produce.
</P>
<P>
By mid-1995, the number of rural people living in income
poverty fell to 65 million, presenting a 75 percent decrease of
poverty-plagued population in less than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
However, China still faces the following challenges in the
fields as follows:
</P>
<P>
-- Up to a third of rural population has an inadequate supply
of drinking water -- 130 million people use untreated surface
water contaminated by domestic, industrial or agro-chemical
wastes, and 43 million people live in water-scarce areas;
</P>
<P>
-- 97 percent of the rural population do not have access to
adequate sanitation;
</P>
<P>
-- health services in poor rural areas are still inferior to
those in cities;
</P>
<P>
-- more than 2 million children were not enrolled in school in
1991-92;
</P>
<P>
Though China has achieved great progress in recent decades,
there is a long way to go before China eliminates income poverty
-- and even further before it eradicates human poverty, UNDP
report stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
