<HEADLINE> Vehicle Theft on Increase in Swaziland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 12 (Xinhua) -- An unprecedented surge in
violent vehicle hijackings in Swaziland has prompted police to
launch a series of spot roadblocks and vehicle searches in the
land-locked kingdom, a local press report said today.
</P>
<P>
Swazi police spokesman Victor Dlamini said in Mbabane, capital
of the kingdom, that 107 of 299 vehicles stolen since January
were taken at gun point, reported African Eye News Service.
</P>
<P>
Dlamini said the Royal Swazi Police had already recovered 165
of the 299 stolen vehicles, an over 50 percent recovery rate.
</P>
<P>
"The worst month for vehicle theft this year is January, when
thieves stole 69 cars and for some reason during May, when they
took 65 vehicles," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Swazi police cracked a syndicate channelling stolen
cars from southern Africa to as far afield as Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Because of the trans-national nature of the thieves'
opeations, countries in the region have recently established a
"frontlie" crack police squad to combat vehicle theft syndicates.
</P>
<P>
The squad comprises officers from South Africa, Zimbabwe,
Mozambique and Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
