<HEADLINE> Consumer Prices Rise in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria recorded a 3.9 percent
price increase in March from the previous month, the Federal
Office of Statistics (FOS) said today.
</P>
<P>
The composite consumer price index (CPI), a measurement of FOS
for consumer price rises, stood at 2830.7 in March, according to
the latest edition of Statistical News, a FOS publication.
</P>
<P>
The government agency attributed the rise to significant
increases in the prices of food items and in the cost of
services.
</P>
<P>
In March, urban and rural indices registered increases of 2.8
percent and 4.4 percent, respectively, as against February, it
said.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the same period last year, the average annual
rate of rise of consumer retail prices moved up by 22.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The composite food index rose by 5.7 percent due to "substantial
increases in the prices of the staple food, vegetables and
fruits."
</P>
<P>
The "all items excluding farm produce" index rose slightly by
0.9 percent in March as against a decline in February.
</P>
<P>
The agency said the March CPI figure also indicated that the
retail prices of goods and services purchased by consumers in
both urban and rural areas rose by 28.3 times between September
1985 and March this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
