<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-12 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish President Pledges Support for Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman Demirel
today reaffirmed that his country will extend any kind of support
to Albania's development.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with visiting Albanian Prime Minister
Bashkim Fino, Demirel said that Albania is a friendly country
of Turkey, adding Ankara is willing to help the Albanian people
overcome their current difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Demirel expressed the hope that Albania can play a special role
in promoting peace and stability in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the forthcoming Albanian general elections on June
29, the Turkish president said that he believes that the Albanian
people will heal their wounds through the elections.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Fino said that Albania attaches great importance
to its ties with Turkey, adding that his visit to Ankara will
further enhance friendship and cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Fino also expressed his gratitude for Turkey's
50-million-U.S. dollar aid promise to his country.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Turkish Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan and
Foreign Minister Tansu Ciller also met with Fino, and both of
Erbakan and Ciller expressed Turkey's support for the
turbulence-hit Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that peace in Albania is important for the peace of
the whole region, Erbakan said "we wish the Albanian people to
overcome their present difficulties and to maintain its
integration with Europe."
</P>
<P>
Ciller, also Turkey's deputy prime minister, told Fino that
Turkey hopes that its participation in the multinational
peacekeeping force will contribute to Albania's peace and
stability.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian prime minister, accompanied by cabinet ministers
and other senior officials, arrived here on Wednesday for a
two-day official visit to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the aim of Fino's Ankara tour is to
seek economic aid from the Turkish government to boost his
country's sluggish economy.
</P>
<P>
The high-ranking Albanian delegation also wants Turkey to
increase its investments in Albania and to help reconstruct its
armed forces, which is described by Fino as almost totally
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
At present, Turkey has 850 troops in Albania, as part of the
6,000-strong multinational peacekeeping troops stationed there to
assist local army and police in keeping order.
</P>
<P>
Political turmoil has brought Albania, the poorest country in
Europe, to the brink of a civil war recently and also caused serious
refugee problem, which aroused grave concern from the
international community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
