<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Treasury Department Unveils New Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Treasury Department
unveiled a new 50-dollar bill today aimed at preventing
counterfeiting.
</P>
<P>
The new currency, to be issued this fall, is the second batch
of U.S. currency to include new and modified security features to
stay ahead of advances in reprographic technology. The newly
designed 100-dollar bill was issued in March 1996.
</P>
<P>
The 50-dollar bills will replace the older series gradually as
they reach U.S. Federal Reserve banks. About 46.5 billion dollars
in 50-dollar notes are in circulation.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the large number "50" on the back of the
notes, the redesigned bills include:
</P>
<P>
--A larger portrait of President Ulysses Grant, moved
off-center to create space for a watermark to the right which can
be seen only when held up to light.
</P>
<P>
--A security thread to the right of the portrait that glows
yellow when exposed to ultraviolet light. "USA FIFTY" and a flag,
which contains microprinting, are printed on the thread.
</P>
<P>
--Color-shifting ink in the numeral on the lower right-hand
corner of the bill front that changes from green to black when
viewed from different angles.
</P>
<P>
--Microprinting in the border and in Grant's shirt collar.
</P>
<P>
--Concentric fine-line printing in the background of the
portrait and on the back of the note.
</P>
<P>
--The engraving of the Capitol on the new bill has been
enlarged to include more detail and reflects a contemporary view
of the west front of the building.
</P>
<P>
"With this redesign, government demonstrates its ability to
stay ahead of the technology curve and meet the needs of all those
people around the world who use and trust our currency," U.S.
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said in a ceremony at the Bureau
of Engraving and Printing.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the introduction of the new 100-dollar bill was
extremely effective against counterfeiters using advanced
technologies including color copiers, scanners and printers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
