<HEADLINE> Brazil to Boost Trade Tie With Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Brazil is planning to boost its
trade tie with Angola which is undergoing national economic
reconstruction after the end of the 20-year-old civil war.
</P>
<P>
This was expressed by Brazilian Ambassador to Angola, Addor
Neto, in addressing a trade forum titled "The Brazilian Economic
System and the Brazil-Angola Relations" held here today.
</P>
<P>
Neto also urged Brazilian business people to take advantage of
the peace dividends in Angola and increase investment in the
southern African country.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's average annual trade volume reached 300 million U.S.
Dollars from 1980 to 1991. It decreased to only one third of the
level in 1992 when civil war was rekindled.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral trade tie started to recover in 1996 when a 185
million-U.S.-Dollar trade volume was recorded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
