<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Historian to Head Clinton Race Advisory Board </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today named a prominent black historian and former governors of
Mississippi and New Jersey to serve on the advisory board that
will launch his national dialogue on race.
</P>
<P>
A White House official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the seven-member panel includes three whites, two blacks, one
Hispanic and one Korean American. Three are women.
</P>
<P>
The panel will be chaired by Duke University historian John
Hope Franklin, 82, who has conducted extensive research into
racial and economic conditions in the South.
</P>
<P>
The official said Harvard University law professor Christopher
Edley will serve as a consultant to the advisory board. Edley
headed the Clinton administration's review of affirmative action
programs that led to Clinton's "mend it, don't end it" approach.
</P>
<P>
Franklin is the author of "From Slavery to Freedom," widely
considered the definitive account of the black experience in
America.
</P>
<P>
The advisory board will accompany Clinton to California this
weekend, where he will unveil his initiative in a commencement
speech at the University of California in San Diego. The members
will meet informally Friday.
</P>
<P>
The panel's main purpose is to launch a national discussion
about race in a series of town hall meetings.
</P>
<P>
The advisory board will spend a year holding town hall meetings
around the country, gathering information that Clinton will
compile into a report. There will also be monthly events by
Clinton and a White House conference on hate crimes in November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
