<HEADLINE> Uganda's GDP Growth Stands at 5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's growth rate of Gross
Domestic Product (GDP) stood at five percent during the 1996/97
financial year.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Minister of Finance and Economic
Planning Mayanja-Nkangi here today while presenting to parliament
the annual budget for the 1997/98 financial year.
</P>
<P>
The rate is lower than the GDP growth rate of the 1995/96
financial year which stood at 8.2 percent and that of 1994/95 at
10 percent.
</P>
<P>
It is also lower than a 6.5 average registered between 1986
and 1990.
</P>
<P>
Observers here attributed the lower growth to the war against
the rebel Lord's Resistance Army in the north in the previous
financial year.
</P>
<P>
However, Nkangi said that the economy is now moving beyond
rehabilitation and adjustment stage which started in 1987 towards
the development phase.
</P>
<P>
He told the nation that the government is committed to
macro-economic stability and fiscal consolidation, arguing that
the central government expenditure in 1996/97 was contained
within the provisions of the overall macro-economic framework
despite a significant shortfall in revenue.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the government's medium-term development
strategy is to promote economic growth of at least five percent per
annum, sustain macro-economic stability, reduce poverty and
create an enabling and conducive environment for private sector
investment in order to stimulate national economic growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
