<HEADLINE> Uganda's External Debt Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's total stock of external
debt has increased to 3.6 billion U.S. Dollars at the end of
December 1996 from 3.28 billion U.S. Dollars at the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Minister of Finance and Economic
Planning Mayanja-Nkangi here today when presenting to parliament
the annual budget for the 1997/98 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Around 75 percent of the current debt was owed to multilateral
institutions, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the debt burden is moving towards sustainable levels
as a result of the debt relief initiatives from international
communities and the government's efforts to boost exports.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that government's fiscal program for the
next three years will seek to reduce the overall fiscal deficit
to sustainable levels #,to increase government savings, and to
finance essential government expenditures.
</P>
<P>
The government will also provide adequate incentive for the
expansion of the private sector and for improving the efficiency
expenditures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
