<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Defense Ministers Meet to Prepare Madrid Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- NATO's defense ministers of 16
member countries ended here today their semi-annual meeting at
which they were doing the final work to prepare NATO's landmark
summit in Madrid less than a month away.
</P>
<P>
Major topics at today's meeting included the situation in
Bosnia and NATO's peacekeeping mission there, and NATO's plans for
wide-ranging reforms.
</P>
<P>
The defense ministers were briefed at the meeting by General
George Joulwan, the outgoing Supreme Allied Commander Europe of
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, on the first six months of
operations by NATO's peacekeeping Stabilization Force.
</P>
<P>
They also strongly called on all Parties in Bosnia-Herzegovina
to implement the Dayton peace accord "fully and without further
delay."
</P>
<P>
On NATO's internal reform, NATO Secretary General Javier Solana
told a press conference after the meeting that the phased
implementation of the Combined Joint Task Force concept, which
makes the future European-only operation possible, was "proceeding
well."
</P>
<P>
As for the rearrangement of the alliance's command structure,
he said, "Some issues remain to be agreed," referring to the still
unsolved U.S.-France dispute for control of NATO's joint command
headquarters, Allied Forces Southern Europe, in Naples, Italy.
</P>
<P>
France has been demanding the post in the Southern Region,
which is always held by an American general, to be handed over to
a European officer in order to make the European defense identity
more visible within NATO, but the suggestion is rejected by the
U.S.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen told reporters that he had
met with the new French Defense Minister Alain Richard at the
meeting and was told that the French position on this matter had
not changed.
</P>
<P>
Talks between the U.S. and France had been put on hold because
of the French election last week. Cohen said that he was not sure
when the talks would be resumed.
</P>
<P>
On external relations, the ministers worked on the terms of the
new NATO-Russia Council, created by the bilateral accord signed by
Russia and NATO on May 27.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Cohen presented Washington's position on which
countries should be invited to join the alliance in the first wave
at the Madrid summit on July 8 and 9.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.S. wanted only three countries, Poland,
Hungary and the Czech Republic, to be included in the first
accession group.
</P>
<P>
Even though it has already been clear for some time that
Washington favored a smaller enlargement, this move is said to
have shocked some member states, including France, which has
pushed for a broader enlargement.
</P>
<P>
France, together with some southern European NATO states, has
been voicing strong support for membership of Romania and
Slovenia, in an attempt to balance the expansion to the east with
a "southern strategy."
</P>
<P>
This morning, the defense ministers also met as 15 -- without
France -- within NATO's Defense Planning Committee and the Nuclear
Planning Group, discussing routine questions related to the
defense review for the next two years in the integrated military
structure.
</P>
<P>
While welcoming the signing of the NATO-Russia Act, the defense
ministers said they looked forward to reciprocal exchanges with
Russia on nuclear weapons issues, including doctrine and strategy
and consultations on nuclear safety issues.
</P>
<P>
They also renewed their call to Russia to bring to completion
the reductions in its tactical nuclear weapons announced in 1991
and 1992 and to consider making additional significant reductions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
