<HEADLINE> Uganda's Revenue for 1997/98 Expected to Reach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's total revenue for
1997/98 fiscal year is expected to reach 840 billion Ugandan
Shillings (about 840 million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
This was announced bys Minister of Finance and Economic
Planning Mayanja-Nkangi here today while presenting to parliament
the annual budget for the 1997/98 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
This, he said, excludes taxes on the government and donor
funded procurements.
</P>
<P>
He said, of this total, 829 billion Shillings are expected to
be generated locally from the Uganda Revenue Authority (URA)
collections and other taxes. The balance of 11 billion Shillings
will come from appropriations in aid.
</P>
<P>
However, for the first time, this year's budget speech
contained no increment in salaries of civil servants.
</P>
<P>
For this, Nkangi explained that the combination of revenue
shortfall, the local government elections to be held in September
this year and the doubling of primary school enrolment in 1997
mean that all areas of government will have to make some
sacrifices.
</P>
<P>
In the budget proposals, Nkangi said the objectives
of the 1997/98 financial year revenue strategies are:
</P>
<P>
1. to revamp the administration of URA;
</P>
<P>
2. to simplify, modernise and consolidate tax-laws;
</P>
<P>
3. to make some significant reforms in taxation, to
promote trade liberalisation, international competitiveness and
relief on poverty;
</P>
<P>
And to make a substantial move fowards having a more
imform, more transparent and much simpler tax system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
