<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Supports Three New Members in NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today announced his support for Poland, Hungary and the Czech
Republic to join the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) in
the first wave of its expansion.
</P>
<P>
"After careful consideration, I've decided that the United
States will support inviting three countries -- Poland, Hungary
and the Czech Republic -- to begin accession talks to join NATO
when we meet in Madrid next month," said President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that Clinton formally expressed support
for the three to join NATO first. Some Western European nations
insist that Romania and Slovenia should also be included in the
first group.
</P>
<P>
"We have said all along that we would judge aspiring members by
their ability to add strength to the alliance and their readiness
to shoulder the obligations of NATO membership," Clinton said in
the written statement.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic
clearly meet those criteria and have currently made the greatest
strides in military capacity and political and economic reform.
</P>
<P>
However, Clinton said that the door for NATO membership will be
open.
</P>
<P>
"As I have repeatedly emphasized, the first new members should
not and will not be the last. We will continue to work with other
interested nations such as Slovenia and Romania to help them
prepare for membership," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Other nations are making good progress, and none will be
excluded from consideration," he added.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of Defense William Cohen formally presented to
the allies the U.S. position today at the defense ministers'
meeting in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Asked why Clinton decided to announce the support until today,
White House spokesman Michael McCurry said, "Achieving consensus
is helped by the United States clarifying publicly its views."
</P>
<P>
"It's clear in the discussions we've had so far that there
are no objections to these three entrants," McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
In the case of Slovenia, McCurry said that it still is in a
position where there is more they can do to fully demonstrate the
military capacity to join the alliance and to fulfill the military
obligations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Romania, McCurry said the country needs "some
progress" in both economic areas and the political reform process.
</P>
<P>
NATO is expected to convene a special summit in July in Madrid
to choose the first group of countries that it will accept as its
new members by 1999.
</P>
<P>
In Brussels, Cohen cited three main reasons for limiting the
Madrid invitations to three: the smaller the initial expansion,
the more cohesiveness NATO will retain; the bigger the expansion,
the higher the bills; concern that the initial expansion not be
perceived as the last. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
