<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Seeks U.N. Chief's Help in Pressing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has called on
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to stop the U.S. from causing
the delay in the approval of Iraqi oil-for-food contracts,
according to the Iraqi News Agency (INA).
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Annan released by INA today, Iraq's Foreign
Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf asked the U.N. chief "to urge
the government of the United States to stop using the (U.N.)
Sanctions Committee as a tool to delay the approval of the
contracts through presenting unfounded and unnecessary pretexts."
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf accused the U.S. representative to the Sanctions
Committee of "delaying the approval of the contracts to achieve
ill-intentioned political goals and thus prolonging the
sufferings of the Iraqi people who have been living under a
comprehensive embargo for seven years now."
</P>
<P>
The letter, dated June 11, said that during the first six
months of the oil-for-food deal, the U.S. representative to the
committee suspended 166 contracts out of 669 presented to the
committee's secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food deal, which signed in May last year, allows
Iraq to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars of oil over six months on a
renewable basis to buy humanitarian goods for its people who were
hit by the U.N.-imposed sanctions on Iraq since its 1990 invasion
of Kuwait. It has been renewed for another six months from June 7.
</P>
<P>
However, every contract for such goods signed by Iraq and
foreign companies must be approved unanimously by the
U.N. Sanctions Committee in advance, consisting of representatives
of all the 15 U.N. Security Council members.
</P>
<P>
As a permanent security council member, the U.S. insists that
the U.N. impose tight control to make sure the supplies are
distributed fairly and not used for military purpose. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
