<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Finalises EPO Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic
Committee (IOC) has finalised its test to detect the drug
erythropoietin (EPO), IOC member Jacques Rogge said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The test is ready, EPO can be traced but we still need to
cover ourselves better legally," Rogge told the Belgian Het
Nieuwsblad newspaper in an interview.
</P>
<P>
Rogge, who is also chairman of the federation of European
National Olympic Committees, said "the door will certainly be
closed" for EPO users at the 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
EPO, which stimulates the production of red blood cells which
transport oxygen around the body, is considered one of the most
dangerous drugs. Extended use can thicken the blood and cause
heart attacks, studies have shown.
</P>
<P>
Belgian Rogge said there was also a 50 percent chance that the
human growth hormone, seen as the ideal substitute for steroids,
could be traced by Sydney 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
