<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Composer Hails Hong Kong's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 13 (Xinhua) -- A well-known Japanese composer is
hailing Hong Kong's return to China as an important event of the
century.
</P>
<P>
During an interview with Xinhua today, Ikuma Dan, chairman of
the Japan-China Cultural Exchanges Association, said Hong Kong's
return signifies that China has expunged a 150-year disgrace
suffered since the Opium War.
</P>
<P>
It has been China's consistent stance that the Hong Kong issue
should be resolved through peaceful talks and the concept of "one
country, two systems" has been devised, he said, acknowledging
that he had much admiration for it.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is famous for its active cultural activities in such
sectors as music, films, drama and the press, and it will play a
bigger role in cultural exchanges between Japan and China, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
