<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5.1 PC Growth Rate Projected for Agriculture Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 13 (Xinhua) -- A growth rate of 5.1 percent has
been projected for the agriculture sector in the Annual
Development Plan for 1997-98 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The agriculture sector registered a growth rate of only 0.7
percent during 1996-97 fiscal year as against the budget target of
5.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
An amount of 487.4 million rupees (about 12.2 million US
dollars) has been allocated in the 1997-98 budget for the
agriculture sector of the Public Sector Development Program
(PSDP).
</P>
<P>
No new project has been included in PSDP due to financial
constraints.
</P>
<P>
The major development programs to be implemented during the new
fiscal year beginning from July 1 are continuation of on-going
projects relating to agriculture research, education, extension
and fisheries.
</P>
<P>
The production targets for cotton, sugarcane, rice and maize
for 1997-98 have been fixed at 10.0 million bales, 48.0 and 4.4
and 1.5 million tonnes, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The new fiscal year has been declared as "Wheat Year" in order
to achieve self-sufficiency in food and wheat target has been
fixed as 18.0 million tonnes.
</P>
<P>
Special emphasized will be laid for increasing the production
of edible oilseeds in order to reduce import of edible oil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Women's Status Rising, Problems Still Remain: Survey (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 13 (Xinhua) -- A recent official survey indicates
that Chinese women's political and social status has risen
steadily over the years, yet their legitimate rights must be
further protected by law.
</P>
<P>
The presence of Chinese women in the political arena has become
more and more common, and their personal rights and those of their
employment and education are well ensured, according to the survey
on how the Law on the Protection of Women's Rights and Interests
is being enforced by local governments.
</P>
<P>
Because the social and economic situations are changing fast
and conditions differ in various locations, women's rights are not
fully protected and in some places are seriously violated, the
survey shows.
</P>
<P>
Three survey groups were sent to provinces of Shanxi, Sichuan
and Guangdong last month by the Civil and Judicial Affairs
Committee under the National People's Congress (NPC). Five other
provinces were ordered to conduct self-examinations and
self-evaluations.
</P>
<P>
They presented their results to a committee meeting attended by
senior lawmaker and top women's rights activist Chen Muhua, who
is vice-chairwoman of the NPC Standing Committee and president of
the All-China Women's Federation.
</P>
<P>
It was reported at the meeting that the number and ratio of
women officials and deputies to people's congresses are up in all
the provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions surveyed.
</P>
<P>
A breakthrough has been made in Shanxi Province, where for many
years there had not been a female official at the provincial level
in the provincial government. And a female city party chief, a
female mayor and a female head of the prefectural people's
congress have been selected in the province.
</P>
<P>
In Sichuan Province, there are one to two percent more deputies
to township, county and provincial people's congresses than in the
previous term of office.
</P>
<P>
Women may be especially hard-hit by the wave of reforms to
unprofitable state enterprises, according to reports at the
meeting. To help re-employ laid-off women, local governments have
encouraged the development of the service sector and tried to find
other employment avenues for women.
</P>
<P>
Following these measures, Changzhi County of Shanxi Province
hired more women, and now females comprise 47 percent of its total
work force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Women's Status Rising, Problems Still Remain: Survey (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To curb sex discrimination against women in the workplace,
local governments have set rules demanding that employers hire a
designated percentage of women. The number of female workers in
Sichuan Province, for the first time in history, increased faster
than that of the males.
</P>
<P>
All the reports claimed provincial governments have emphasized
the need to safeguard women's rights to personal safety, and
equality in marriage, family and possessions. As a result of
China's "Strike Hard" anti-crime campaign, the crimes of
kidnapping women and the number of women abducted have decreased
in the past two years in Sichuan.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong Province sentenced 79.6 percent of the criminals
convicted of cruelly injuring or killing women to five or more
years in prison, or even execution, in accordance with the law.
</P>
<P>
Many places have formulated specific rules and regulations to
ensure equality between men and women.
</P>
<P>
In terms of education, statistics from the places surveyed show
that more than 97 percent of the eligible female children are now
in school. In prosperous Guangdong Province, the number of
illiterate women is near zero.
</P>
<P>
But the gender gap still exists. For instance, according to the
reports, women's involvement in politics is at a
far-from-satisfactory level, women are still discriminated in
workplaces, and their situations in overseas, private and township
enterprises have not been improved.
</P>
<P>
In some places, family violence is up, and bigamist marriages
and extra-marital affairs are becoming prevalent.
</P>
<P>
After listening to these reports, Chen Muhua said, "We may
fully affirm our achievements in protecting the rights and
interests of women, but should never overestimate them."
</P>
<P>
She believed the most effective solution for all the problems
found in the survey is to educate society about the Law on the
Protection of Women's Rights and Interests.
</P>
<P>
"By doing so, we may make women realize that they can resort to
legal means to tackle their problems, and let men be aware that
the problems of the opposite sex are not only the problems of
individuals, but of the whole society," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that the key segment of those to be educated
should be officials of the male sex. Women's organizations and
activists should forward their suggestions on specific matters,
she added.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the ongoing national move to promote ethical and
cultural progress should also focus on the issues of bigamy and
extra-marital affairs, for they are serious moral and social
problems, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
The sexual revolution in the West has produced some harmful
trends that should be prevented, and some of China's own backward
customs should be reformed to protect the equality of sexes, she
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0079 </DOCNO>
