<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> About 70 PC of Pakistan's New Budget Goes to Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government today
presented the 1997-98 budget with allocation of 69.2 percent of
the total resources for debt servicing and defense.
</P>
<P>
According to the budget report, the debt servicing for the new
fiscal year is estimated at 247.9 billion rupees (6.2 billion US
dollars), accounting for 44.9 percent of the 1997-98 total budget
outlay of 552 billion rupees (13.8 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The debt servicing for the new fiscal year amounts to about
53.7 percent of the total current expenditure which has been
estimated at 461.9 billion rupees (11.55 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Servicing of domestic debt is estimated at 153.9 billion rupees
(3.85 billion dollars), servicing of foreign debt will be 31.50
billion rupees (788 million dollars), while foreign loan repayment
is expected to be 62.46 billion rupees (1.56 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The defense expenditure for the new financial year has been
estimated at 134 billion rupees (3.35 billion US dollars),
indicating an increase of two percent over the 1996-97 budget
estimates and 5.2 percent over the revised estimates.
</P>
<P>
The defense expenditure accounts for 24.3 percent of the total
budget outlay and 29 percent of the current expenditure for
1997-98.
</P>
<P>
In the 1996-97 budget, defense expenditure was estimated at
131.4 billion rupees (3.28 billion dollars), and it was later
revised at 127.4 billion rupees (3.18 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The defense expenditure accounted for about 26.3 percent of the
total budget outlay for 1996-97 which stood at 500.2 billion
rupees (12.5 billion dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
