<HEADLINE> France Rules Out Intervention in Congo Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 13 (Xinhua) -- France today ruled out any
intervention in the continued fighting in the Congo Republic, or
in joining any kind of interposing force in the country.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt said the
1,200 French soldiers in Congo are "exclusively" for evacuating
foreign expatriates.
</P>
<P>
"This detachment does not have any vocation to intervene in the
fighting or participate in whatever interposing force," he said.
</P>
<P>
Former Congolese President Denis Sassou N'Guesso, who is head
of one side in the fighting, said in a telephone interview with
the French daily "Le Figaro" that an international force should be
deployed to secure the presidential election on July 27.
</P>
<P>
So far French troops have evacuated 3,420 foreign expatriates,
half of them French nationals, from Brazzaville on military
aircraft to neighboring Gabon.
</P>
<P>
Rummelhardt said France agreed to participate in a meeting of
"plenipotentiaries" of Congo as was proposed by Gabonese President
Omar Bongo, to seek a solution to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sassou N'Guesso today accused President Pascal
Lissouba of using Angola's UNITA rebel soldiers as mercenaries to
fend off his "Cobra" militiamen.
</P>
<P>
He said an Antonov aircraft of the Congo air company is
"ensuring regularly the transport of arms between the UNITA zone
of Angola and Pointe-Noire" in western Congo, and a Lebanese man
was running the transport of armaments between Pointe-Noire and
Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
Sassou N'Guesso Thursday asked French troops to stop Lissouba
from receiving reinforcements from the Brazzaville airport.
</P>
</TEXT>
