<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Presents New Law to Beef up CITES </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) today
presented a new wildlife trade legislation aimed at strengthening
the operations of the Convention on International Trade in
Endangered Species (CITES).
</P>
<P>
Head of EU delegation Wim Wessels told the press conference at
the ongoing 10th meeting of the CITES in Harare that the
regulation was a demonstration of its commitment to the CITES.
</P>
<P>
Under the new law which came in to effect on June 1, the
import and export of 30,000 wild plants and animal species and
their products such as ivory, parrots and couriels would be
regulated.
</P>
<P>
Trade controls at EU external borders would be tightened while
internal borders would be abolished.
</P>
<P>
A limited number of ports of entry would be designated for the
import and export of regulated species.
</P>
<P>
Wessels said a massive regional information campaign targeting
travellers, trades and customs agency to inform the European
public of the provision of the new EU legislation subscribe to
full requirements of the CITES with regard to control and
monitoring of trade in selected species.
</P>
<P>
"We feel the arrival of the regulation is an excellent
opportunity for the EU to demonstrate its commitment to the
CITES, its determination to improve its performance and its
commitment to the ratification of the Gaborone amendment," said
Wessels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
