<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Lags Behind in Income, Human Development: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 13 (Xinhua) -- A Nepali expert said here today
that Nepal is the poorest even among South Asian countries not
only in per capita income, but also in most of the key human
indicators, such as adult literacy, mother and child mortality,
food consumption and provision of water and health services.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Kishor Guru-Gharana, a member of the Nepali National
Planning Commission, made a presentation on the 1997 Human
Development Report (HDR) from Nepalese perspective at a press
conference held here by the United Nations Development Programme
to launch the HDR, which focuses on poverty eradication through
human development and other strategies.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Guru-Gharana said Nepal was placed at 151 last year among
174 countries in the world, this year it stands at 154 on a list
of 175 countries, only above Bhutan among the seven South Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
But Nepal lags behind more in human progress than in economic
achievement, noted Dr. Guru-Gharana, saying Nepal has to pay
special attention to gender issues because it is one of the two
exceptional countries in the world with life expectancy of women
less than that of men.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Nepalese women lag far behind men in literacy,
access to education, health services, land and credit, while their
workload is considered one of the largest in the world, on average
about 40 percent larger than men, he said.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Guru-Gharana said in preparation of the Ninth Five Year
Plan (1997-2002), Nepal has given due consideration to the
development strategies suggested in the HDR.
</P>
<P>
For example, the ninth plan gives high attention to ending all
kinds of disparities and discriminations between men and women
through increased access of females to education, health, land and
job opportunities, he said.
</P>
<P>
And the National Planning Commission has listed poverty
eradication within a given time frame through pro-poor growth and
employment -friendly strategies as the overriding objective of the
ninth plan, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
