<HEADLINE> IAAF Likely to Issue Wild Cards for Johnson and Others </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 13 (Xinhua) -- World athletics governing body IAAF
is likely to offer "wild card" invitations to Michael Johnson and
other top U.S. athletes who don't qualify for the World
Championships.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here, USA Track and Field said
Thursday it would support the move if the International Amateur
Athletic Federation awarded wild cards for the Aug. 1-10 world
championships in Athens, Greece.
</P>
<P>
"This is like an open door,"' IAAF spokesman Giorgio Reineri
said Friday. "It's now in the hands of the IAAF to decide. The IAAF
has the possibility to invite the reigning world champions, and
maybe the world record-holder."
</P>
<P>
IAAF president Primo Nebiolo has said he is not against the idea.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. team for the World Championships is determined by the
U.S. nationals, which are being held this week in Indianapolis. The
first three finishers in most events qualify.
</P>
<P>
But many big stars such like Johnson, Dan O'Brien, Gwen
Torrence, Mike Powell and Carl Lewis are among the top names
missing from the nationals.
</P>
<P>
Johnson, the 1995 world champion and 1996 Olympic gold medalist
in the 200 and 400 meters, is out with a strained left quadriceps
suffered during his 150-match race agianst Donovan Bailey on June 1.
</P>
<P>
O'Brien, the three-time world champion and Olympic gold medalist
in the decathlon, missed the national championships because of a
stress fracture of the right tibia. 
</P>
