<HEADLINE> Germany's Economic Growth Continues in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The German economy continued to grow
in the second quarter of this year, but will have to expand
further in order to meet the government target for a 2.5 percent
growth for the year as a whole, officials said today.
</P>
<P>
The June economic report of the German Economics Ministry
Friday did not mention any figure for second quarter growth, but
said conditions for a further acceleration of the economy "remain
favorable".
</P>
<P>
There were expansions both in foreign orders and domestic
demand, the report said. Production was also clearly above the
level of last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the report also registered continuing weakness in
private consumption and a slack construction sector.
</P>
<P>
Germany's gross domestic product (GDP) expanded by 1.4 percent
in the first quarter of this year after zero growth in the fourth
quarter of 1996. The latest report of the Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) predicted that the
German economy would grow by 2.2 percent in 1997 and 2.8 percent
in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
