<HEADLINE> France, Germany to Urge NATO's Admission of Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 13 (Xinhua) -- France and Germany are expected to
jointly propose to the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
that it admits Romania as a member.
</P>
<P>
French officials attending the Franco-German summit today in
Poitiers, south-central France, said President Jacques Chirac and
Chancellor Helmut Kohl are "reflecting on" a joint proposal, which
also calls for the admission of another unnamed country, most
probably Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
The reflection came after a surprise announcement by the United
States that only Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic can enter
NATO in the first wave of NATO expansion.
</P>
<P>
Chirac and Kohl discussed the issue of security and defense
soon after they began their meeting, with French Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin present.
</P>
<P>
United States Secretary of Defense William Cohen said in
Brussels Thursday that President Bill Clinton's primary concern
was to ensure a two-thirds majority in the U.S. Senate, which is
required to ratify any enlargement of the alliance.
</P>
<P>
He said the American position is "non-negotiable."
</P>
<P>
Germany has so far restrained from publicly expressing its view
on which countries should join NATO in the first wave. France has
supported the candidacy of Romania for a long time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Index for China-Affiliated Companies on HK's Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Hang Seng Index (HSI) Services
Limited announced here on Friday the launch of a new index, the
Hang Seng China-Affiliated Corporations Index, on June 16 this
year, which is to track the performance of locally-listed
companies with a significant equity interest held by entities in
China.
</P>
<P>
The new index comprises 32 constituent stocks which have at
least 35 percent of their share holding held, directly or
indirectly, by state-owned organizations or provincial or
municipal authorities in China.
</P>
<P>
The stocks should have been listed for at least 12 months on
The Stock Exchange of Hong Kong Limited and have a trading record
of at least 12 months under the control of the Chinese entities.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the stocks must not be constituent stocks of the
Hang Seng China Enterprises Index, which includes locally-listed
state-owned enterprises in China.
</P>
<P>
"There has been growing investors' interest in China-affiliated
companies listed on the Hong Kong stock market. This is reflected
by the increase in the market capitalization of the companies
covered by the Index from 2.7 percent at the end of May 1996 to
6.4 percent at the end of May 1997, and by the growth in their
turnover from 4.1 percent to 15.5 percent over the same period,"
said Anthony Wong, Chairman of HSI Limited.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong is the seventh-largest stock market in the world and
the second-largest in Asia after Japan. Strategically located in
southern China, Hong Kong is the gateway for foreign companies to
expand into China's inland areas. With its sophisticated
financial infrastructure, Hong Kong has also become an important
fund-raising center for companies in China's inland," Wong said.
</P>
<P>
"The Hang Seng China-Affiliated Corporations Index is designed
to meet the increasing demand for a benchmark to gauge the
performance of China-affiliated companies listed on the stock
market," he said.
</P>
<P>
Each of the constituent stocks of the new index is weighted so
that it will influence the Index proportion to its respective
market value. The market value weightings will be updated on a
monthly basis.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng China-Affiliated Corporations Index is backdated
to January 4, 1993 with a base value of 1,000. The Index stood at
2,490.20 at the close of business on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
From June 16, 1997, the Index will be released on a
minute-by-minute basis on each trading day. It will be widely
disseminated through international and local data services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
