<HEADLINE> U.S. Hurdler Barred from U.S. Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 13 (Xinhua) -- World athletics governing body IAAF
said Friday that American hurdler Stephon Flenoy remains suspended
and is not authorized to run in the U.S. national championships.
</P>
<P>
The International Amateur Athletic Federation said it would
invoke its "contamination rule" in the Flenoy case, meaning that
any athlete who competes against him risks being suspended, a
report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The warning came one day after Flenoy, a 400-meter hurdler who
allegedly failed a drug test last year, was reinstated by an
American arbitrator in time to compete in the U.S. nationals in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
Flenoy had elevated levels of the hormone testosterone in a
urine sample taken at last year's U.S. Olympic trials. He was
suspended by USA Track and Field on April 4, and the IAAF
announced its own suspension on May 31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
