<HEADLINE> Pak Government Presents 1997-98 National Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government led by
Nawaz Sharif today presented the budget for 1997-98 fiscal year
with a total outlay of 552 billion rupees (13.8 billion US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The budget size for the new financial year is 10.4 percent
higher than the budget estimates of 500.2 billion rupees (12.5
billion dollars) for 1996-97 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The budget, presented by Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz at the
National Assembly this afternoon, was the first by the Sharif
government since it came to power in February this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the budget, the resource availability during the
new financial year has been estimated at 487.4 billion rupees
(12.18 billion dollars) as compared to 480.42 billion rupees
(12.01 billion dollars) the current fiscal year, indicating an
increase of 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Net revenue receipts for 1997-98 have been estimated at 326
billion rupees (8.15 billion dollars) which indicate an increase
of 1.6 percent over 1996-97 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The net capital receipts for 1997-98 are expected to be 27.9
billion rupees (697.5 million dollars), an increase of five
percent over the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Financing by the local governments for Public Sector
Development Program will be 3.859 billion rupees (96.5 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, receipts from external resources in 1997-98 are
estimated to be 129.5 billion rupees (3.24 billion dollars),
showing an increase of 26.5 percent over 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
The budget shortfall for 1997-98 has been estimated at 64.6
billion rupees (1.62 billion dollars) compared to 88.64 billion
rupees (2.22 billion dollars) in the revised budget estimates of
1996-97, showing a decrease of 27 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
