<HEADLINE> Pakistan's Current Expenditure for 1997-98 Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's current expenditure
for 1997-98 financial year has been estimated at 461.9 billion
rupees (11.55 billion US dollars), an increase of about 17 percent
over 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
The share of current expenditure in the total budget outlay for
1997-98 is 83.7 percent compared to 79.1 percent in the 1996-97
budget.
</P>
<P>
The expenditure on running of the civil government during the
new fiscal year is estimated at 46.4 billion rupees (1.16 billion
dollars) as compared to 47.3 billion rupees (1.18 billion dollars)
in 1996-97 budget estimates, indicating a decrease of two percent.
</P>
<P>
The size of Public Sector Development Program for 1997-98 is
estimated at 90.1 billion rupees (2.25 billion dollars). This
shows an increase of 5.8 percent over the revised estimates of
85.2 billion rupees (2.13 billion dollars) for 1996-97 and a
decrease of 14 percent over the 1996-97 budget estimates.
</P>
