<HEADLINE> Chinese Minister Outlines Communications Cooperation With HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Wu Jichuan, Chinese minister of
Posts and Telecommunications, said here today that after the
return of Hong Kong, the central department in charge of
communications will continue to cooperate with its Hong Kong
counterparts and expand operations, by adhering to the principle
of equality and consultation.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Wu said the communications affairs
of Hong Kong will be administered by the government of the Hong
Kong Special Administration Region (SAR) itself after July 1.
</P>
<P>
The central department in charge of communications and its Hong
Kong counterparts will not be subordinate to each other, and no
posts and telecommunications departments in the inland areas may
interfere in affairs that the SAR shall administer on its own, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Wu said the staff in posts and telecommunications departments
at various levels are now carrying out numerous activities to
greet the return of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
To mark the historic event, the Chinese Ministry of Posts and
Telecommunications started in 1995 to issue three sets of stamps
reflecting Hong Kong's scenery, economic development, and the
return, he added.
</P>
<P>
Entrusted by some relevant state departments, the ministry has
also shouldered the work of designing and printing the first set
of stamps for the Hong Kong SAR, he said.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the exchanges and cooperations between the inland
areas and Hong Kong in the field of communications, Wu said both
sides have not only maintained close ties in the communications
network and business, but also been successful in communication
development, technical exchanges and personnel training.
</P>
<P>
He cited such cities as Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, Tianjin,
Haikou, Fuzhou, Xiamen, Nanning and Shenzhen as having been
installed with a direct electric circuit linking Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In addition to traditional communications business, digital
mobile telephone roaming systems, and telephone cards have become
available between Hong Kong and the inland areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
Wu said the status of Hong Kong as an international financial
and trade center is closely related to its status as an
international information center.
</P>
<P>
After the return of Hong Kong, communications departments of
both sides will increase cooperation and offer a better
communication service for the prosperity of the two sides, he said.
</P>
<P>
In referring to the Hong Kong investors involved in the
communications issue, Wu said his ministry will follow relevant
policies, encourage the Hong Kong businessmen to invest in some
specific projects with the prerequisite that they will not
participate in management, and give returns to the investors.
</P>
<P>
Given the unique situation of Hong Kong after its return, the
Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications will study how to further
absorb investment from the region, and offer preferential
treatment to Hong Kong investors, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
