<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Bans Use of CFCs in Aerosol Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 13 (Xinhua) -- China announced today that after
December 31, 1997, all aerosol product manufacturers should stop
using chloroflourocarbons (CFCs), substances that seriously damage
the ozone layer.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that the country has banned an industry
from using substances harmful to the ozone.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference here today, nine central government
departments including the State Bureau of Environmental
Protection, the China National Council of Light Industry and the
Ministry of Chemical Industry, jointly issued the notice.
</P>
<P>
The notice said that the government will no longer register
aerosol products using CFCs after January 1, 1998, and no
factories that manufacturing such products will be approved to be
set up.
</P>
<P>
The factories that have already been established will be dealt
with according to the law, the notice added.
</P>
<P>
The ban also prohibits the planning and economic departments at
all levels from approving projects that deal with the aerosol
products that contain CFCs.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that the bulk of the aerosol products used
currently in daily life such as mousse, cosmetics and pesticide
contain CFCs, damage the ozone layer upon entering the atmosphere,
which in turn allows more ultraviolet rays to reach the earth's
surface.
</P>
<P>
Experts here said that the increase in ultraviolet rays will
lead to higher incidence of cancer and cataracts, will lower
people's immunity to disease and adversely affect crop yields.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that the country has decided to replace CFCs with
liquefied petroleum gas and dimethyl ether in the aerosol
industry, and to supervise the industry's products that formerly
used CFCs.
</P>
<P>
"Enterprises that violate the ban will be punished," officials
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
