<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Holds Talks with Partner Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Defense ministers of the 16 NATO
states started today in Brussels an one-day meeting with their
counterparts from the alliance's 27 partner countries in the
framework of the newly established Euro-Atlantic Partnership
Council (EAPC).
</P>
<P>
The EAPC was formally launched two weeks ago in Sintra,
Portugal, at NATO's foreign ministers' meeting, with the aim of
promoting the political dialogue and military cooperation between
NATO and its partner countries.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech at the meeting, NATO Secretary General
Javier Solana said that the new security body "has great promise,
offers new opportunities and carries with it new challenges".
</P>
<P>
He briefed the defense ministers from partners countries on the
outcome of NATO's defense ministers'' meeting on Thursday and the
development of the practical cooperation activities taken place in
the past year.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time for the ministers (from NATO and
partner countries) to discuss in depth the military cooperation in
the enhanced Partnership for Peace (PfP) Program," a NATO
official said.
</P>
<P>
The official said that from now on partner countries would be
actively involved in both planning and implementation of the PfP
activities "right from the beginning".
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Slovenian defense minister Turnsek Tit expressed
disappointment about Thursday's announcement by the United States
that it wanted only Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic to be in
NATO's first expansion, leaving outside Romania and Slovenia which
were strongly supported by a majority of NATO's European alllies,
including France and Italy.
</P>
<P>
"It is unlogical to exclude candidate countries which have
already met the accession criteria to joint in the first group,"
Tit was quoted by the same official as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We hope NATO's open door will open again," the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Prior to today's defense ministers' meeting, Solana has held a
short separate meeting with the first deputy defense minister of
Russia, Andrei Kokoshin.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, which is described by NATO officials as "a
good one", Kokoshin is said to have told Solana that Russian
President Boris Yeltsin was "enthusiastic" to see the early
implementation of "all the aspects" of the Russia-NATO Act, which
was signed by him and leaders of NATO states on May 27 in
Paris. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
