<HEADLINE> Jordan Ratifies Most Labor Conventions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The Jordanian government has
ratified six of the seven labor-related conventions of the
International Labor Organization (ILO), King Hussein of Jordan
said here today.
</P>
<P>
"As to convention No. 87 concerning the freedom of association
and protection of the right of organization, existing Jordanian
legislation has stipulated the protection of freedom and labor
rights as well as the right to organize professional and labor
associations," King Hussein told the 85th International Labor
Conference.
</P>
<P>
He said Jordan had re-examined and reformed its labor policies
in response to technological innovation as well as the changing
regional and international environment.
</P>
<P>
"Our economic re-structuring program is a manifestation of
economic adaptability, and our willingness to achieve the highest
possible degree of self reliance within a well balanced, flexible
and competitive environment to ensure a smooth transition to
higher levels of economic activity," Hussein said.
</P>
<P>
He said that since the promulgation of the Jordanian
constitution, and accession to the ILO in 1956, Jordan's
legislation in employment, vocational and technical training as
well as social security had been influenced by the ILO principles.
</P>
<P>
He said he hoped Jordan and the ILO would improve their
cooperation in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
