<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Budget Ensures Social Justice, Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Finance Minister Shah
AMS Kibria said here today that the proposed budget for 1997-98
has been formulated with the aim to fulfill the election pledges
of the Awami (people's) League government by ensuring social
justice and poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
"We have translated slogans, given for a long time, into
realistic steps by making proposals in the proposed budget for
rural infrastructure and ensuring social justice," he told a
post-budget press conference held here today.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Minister on Thursday night placed in Parliament the
budget for 1997-98 fiscal year, outlaying a total expenditure of
277.86 billion taka (about 6.46 billion U.S. dollars) and leaving
an overall deficit of 81.62 billion taka (about 1.9 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) has turned
down the proposed new budget as "anti-people" and called upon the
people to build a movement against this budget.
</P>
<P>
The BNP alleged that this budget would lead mill, factories,
industries to destruction through encouraging smuggling from
neighboring India.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jatiya (national) Party Chairman HM Ershad, whose
party supported Awami (people's) League to form the government,
has also criticized the new budget and said the present government
will have to bear all its liabilities.
</P>
<P>
Defending his budget, the Finance Minister pointed out that
64.3 billion taka (about 1.49 billion dollars) has been earmarked
for direct and indirect expenditure in the social justice sector.
</P>
<P>
He said under the programme for providing allowance to the
elderly people, 4.5 million senior citizens would be benefited.
</P>
<P>
"This might be a small step but it is for the first time in
Bangladesh that such a measure for ensuring social security has
been proposed," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Minister said the agriculture sector has been given
priority as two-thirds of the country's population are involved in
the sector directly or indirectly.
</P>
<P>
He said, to encourage investment in the agriculture sector, the
1997-98 budget has proposed and allocation of 10 billion taka
(about 232 million dollars) to be disbursed as agricultural loan
under the supervision of the Bangladesh Bank.
</P>
<P>
Besides, in order to generate employment, the budget has
proposed for setting up an "employment Bank" which would provide
assistance to youths for self-employment, he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate of GDP (gross domestic product) in the 1997-98
fiscal is expected to be six percent and within the next five year
it would rise to seven percent, said the Finance Minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
