<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The United States defied most of its NATO allies yesterday
and announced its determination to limit the first wave of the
alliance's expansion to Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
-- Capitulating under political pressure, Congressional
Republicans passed a long-awaited 8.6 billion dollar disaster
relief bill yesterday, but not before the process revealed sharp
divisions within the party's leadership and became a public
relations fiasco reminiscent of the Government shutdown 18 months
ago.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton yesterday named a seven-member advisory
board that will organize town hall meetings, analyse date and
otherwise guide him as he prepares to launch a broad effort to
narrow America's racial divide.
</P>
<P>
-- Federal jurors in the Oklahoma City bombing case who 10 days
ago convicted Timothy J. McVeigh of causing the largest mass
murder in U.S. history yesterday began deliberating whether he
should pay with his life. The panel recessed without reaching a
penalty verdict after meeting most of the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- A Tobacco settlement is moving closer and key players are
preparing to sell a pact to Congress and the public. Meanwhile,
Florida agreed to help the FDA catch retailers selling tobacco to
minors and California became the 37th state to sue the industry.
</P>
<P>
Washington Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The House yesterday overwhelmingly passed a proposed
constitutional amendment aimed at banning the physical desecration
of the U.S. Flag. The vote followed a heated debate over whether
the measure infringes on individual liberties.  
</P>
</TEXT>
