<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 12:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Tourism Minister Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Tourism Minister Bahattin
Yucel resigned today before Welfare Party (RP) Chairman and
Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan's handover of his post to his
junior partner True Path Party (DYP) leader Tansu Ciller.
</P>
<P>
Yucel, a DYP deputy, said at a press conference in parliament
that "Any government model which will include the RP gives
signals that it will turn the growing tension in the country to a
clash."
</P>
<P>
He said that tension created by the RP escalated and new
efforts to find a solution with the participation of the Grand
Unity Party (BBP) will "drag the country along with a new crisis
instead of overcoming the problems."
</P>
<P>
Yucel became the fourth minister to quit the cabinet in less
than two months to pressure Ciller to end the alliance with
Erbakan.
</P>
<P>
Ciller, also deputy prime minister and foreign minister, said
Thursday that Erbakan promised to leave his position and present
his resignation to President Suleyman Demirel on June 18, adding
that on the same day, she will ask the president to assign her
with the task of forming a new government.
</P>
<P>
This means that Ciller will take over power from Erbakan,
one year ahead of schedule set in a bi-partite agreement.
</P>
<P>
The RP and DYP formed the coalition government in 1996 and
signed the power-sharing protocol which stipulated that Erbakan
would head the government for the first two years and then turn
it over to Ciller for the remaining two years.
</P>
<P>
After near one year in power, the government is now faced
with growing impatience with Erbakan's inclination to inch the
country toward an Islamic entity and his reluctance to curb
the fundamentalist force in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The military and opposition regarded Erbakan's policies as a
threat to Turkey's secularism enshrined in its constitution.
</P>
<P>
Ciller and the DYP issued an ultimatum early this month to
Erbakan, asking him to hand out his post before June 18 or to
face a collapse of the coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan and Ciller met with BBP leader Muhsin Yaziciouglu, a
prospective new coalition partner, for several hours Thursday to
seek a way out of the current political crisis.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the three party leaders came amid an
increasing political tension due to another military warning
against the rapidly expanding fundamentalist activities in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
