<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forum Calls for More Western Aid for Africa (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The second Asia-Africa Forum today
urged the international community, Western developed countries in
particular, to continue its help in Africa's economic and social
development.
</P>
<P>
The call is contained in "the message to the Denver Summit of
the Eight" (countries), which was adopted here today before the
forum concluded its three-day meetings.
</P>
<P>
The forum "expressed the hope that the summit will make
significant contributions in support of African development
efforts," the message said.
</P>
<P>
The forum also "urged the participating countries of the Denver
summit to reinforce their support to inter-regional and triangular
cooperation aimed at furthering African development."
</P>
<P>
The forum today also adopted "the Bangkok Statement for
Furthering Asia-Africa Cooperation," which urged African countries
to "intensify the pace of structural transformation of their
economies in order to enhance mutually beneficial relationships
with Asian countries."
</P>
<P>
It noted that trade and investment between Asia and Africa,
though relatively low, have been rising steadily in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The forum emphasized the crucial role of the private sector and
observed that successful economies in Asia and Africa have
implemented policies and strategies conducive to private sector
development.
</P>
<P>
The forum recognized that there were numerous opportunities for
public and private sector cooperation -- the development of
infrastructure, communications, deepening of the financial sector,
managerial and vocational skills training and the promotion of
foreign investment and development of joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
The three-day forum focused on Africa's capacity building
including institutional, political and economic aspects,
sustainable agricultural development and food security and private
sector development.
</P>
<P>
It said agriculture is one of the areas where Asia's experience
and success can be put to use in Africa and that more needs to be
done to expand networks among agricultural institutions and the
private sector of the two continents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
