<HEADLINE> Sweden Helps Zambia Boost Rural Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's rural enterprises will
benefit from a seven-billion-Kwacha economic expansion in
outlying areas (EEOA) project sponsored by the Swedish
International Development Agency (SIDA).
</P>
<P>
The 5.38-million-U.S.-Dollar project aims at improving the
rural dwellers' economic base by creating infrastructure and
fostering a sense of ownership among the stakeholders, according
to a project brief.
</P>
<P>
The EEOA is already in operation in Northern and Eastern
provinces.
</P>
<P>
However, this is not a handout type of project as partakers
will have to contribute 20 percent of the total cost for a
individual project either in case or in kind.
</P>
<P>
One of the components of the EEOA is the credit guarantee fund
aimed at helping rural entrepreneurs access to capital from
commercial financial institutions as well as assist new viable
projects in target areas.
</P>
<P>
Because of past experience in loan recovery, the risk factor
of lending will be shared between the bank and the EEOA project
to guarantee that all efforts will be made to recover the loans.
</P>
<P>
In this case, the credit guarantee fund will only consider
medium and small scale entrepreneurs with a proven record of
sound financial management. The bank will also only consider
applications for viable projects.
</P>
<P>
The EEOA program will provide management training for
successful applicants as they may require. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0129 </DOCNO>
