<HEADLINE> Private Telecom Company to Start Operation in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- A foreign private
telecommunications company, Telecel, will start operation late
this month in Zambia, "Times of Zambia" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Telecel Commercial Director Clive Shamwana said here on
Thursday that the company will provide competition to the
parastatal monopoly, Zamtel and assured customers of unmatched
service and lower costs.
</P>
<P>
"We are here in a big positive way. Our aim is to broaden
telecommunication services in Zambia. We are backed by our global
capacity as one of the largest telecommunications companies in
the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
Telecel has entered into an inter-connection agreement with
Zamtel so that customers receive and send calls regardless of the
origin or whether they are connected to Zamtel facility or to
Telecel facility.
</P>
<P>
He said customers will enjoy 10 to 20 percent lower telephone
charges than at present. 
</P>
