<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Chinese Woman Judge And Her Juvenile Delinquents (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Cheng was punished for petty theft
when he was 15. Now he is studying at a key university in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"Without Aunt Shang's help, it would be impossible for me to
have this opportunity," Cheng said with his voice quivering.
</P>
<P>
"Aunt Shang" is Shang Xiuyun, a judge dealing with juvenile
delinquents at Beijing's Haidian District People's Court.
</P>
<P>
Shang, 54, is one of China's first generation of judges devoted
to juvenile cases. In the past decade she has seen many sorry
scenes in her court, and has enthusiastically directed a large
number of youngsters back on a meaningful path in life.
</P>
<P>
Twelve youngsters Shang has dealt with have been accepted as
students by some of the best universities including Beijing and
Qinghua universities, while a further 18 have studied at key
vocational schools and secondary schools. Moreover, 99 percent of
the delinquents whose cases have been dealt with by Shang have
firmly broken away from their criminal pasts.
</P>
<P>
The new lives of the 170-plus youngsters are closely connected
to Shang's determination and dedication to offer them help.
</P>
<P>
Haidian District has the greatest concentration of schools in
Beijing. The number of secondary schools there alone exceeds 120.
</P>
<P>
An official said that the District People's Court handles about
one-third of the city's juvenile cases every year.
</P>
<P>
"To punish isn't a judge's aim," Shang says.
</P>
<P>
"I should help these youngsters," Shang told herself on the
first day that she handled juvenile cases 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Some of them were up in court for stealing a designer T-shirt,
others a book, while a few stole bikes, maybe to sell and raise
cash for a birthday party or present.
</P>
<P>
One reason they committed these petty crimes was that they were
never given the necessary attention, care, help and education from
their family and society, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Government Urged to Draw Up New Aviation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has been
urged to formulate a new aviation policy to bring maximum
benefits to Zambia, according to "Zambia Daily Mail".
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper today quoted a civil aviation official as
saying here on Thursday that the government has at many times
pronounced a liberalized policy in air transport but without
legal framework for implementing it.
</P>
<P>
Sam Namukombo, AERO Zambia special assistant to the managing
director, said that Zambia has yet to formulate a comprehensive
long term aviation policy, which could be monitored and managed
by a national civil aviation board.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's registered airlines' role in the socio-economic
development is unspecified and therefore the government should
take into account the rapid changes taking place in a number of
countries to take measures, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said civil aviation in Zambia is still guided by two
outdated laws and this scenario is now giving problems to other
foreign airlines operating air services to and from Lusaka
International Airport in respect of the provision of ground
handling services, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Chinese Woman Judge And Her Juvenile Delinquents (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On one occasion Shang invited a defendant's mother to the court
room in order to make an emotional impression on the accused.
</P>
<P>
Once she had formally pronounced the court's decision, she
shouted with emotion, "Lad, just look at your mother... look at
her... It's clear that she works her hands to the bone to care for
you!"
</P>
<P>
Ashamed, the pathetic lad knelt down at the feet of his mother
as tears rolled down his cheeks. "Mother, I'll improve. I'll..."
</P>
<P>
At that moment, many in the court room were overcome with this
emotional scene.
</P>
<P>
To keep track of the youngsters after they exit the courts,
Shang holds files on each of them. She calls them on the phone and
sometimes meets them. It's time consuming, but worth it, she said.
</P>
<P>
To a certain extent this dedicated, motherly judge has become a
real aunt. Shang has all the childrens' birthdays noted down, and
phones them to give her best wishes on their big days, always
encouraging them to make further, honest progress.
</P>
<P>
"The kids seem willing to tell Shang what's on their minds, and
many actually call her Aunt," the judge's assistant Lu Haifei said.
</P>
<P>
Shang is also mother to two of her own children. But sometimes
they feel neglected.
</P>
<P>
"I'll never forget my daughter's angry words to me one
night. She roared at me, 'other children can have meals with their
father and mother at night, but not me. You often forget my
birthday, but always remember theirs'. Who is your child?" Shang
recalled her daughter as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Actually, delinquents do need more love and care," Shang said.
</P>
<P>
In an educational show room attached to the court, there is a
sculpture, appropriately and simply named "Hand". It was given to
Shang by one juvenile offender.
</P>
<P>
It symbolizes the countless, helping hands she has held out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leonean Parliamentarians Ask Military to Step </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Parliamentarians in Sierra Leone on
Thursday released a mediation plan calling on the ruling junta to
step down, according to a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The Armed Forces Revolutionary Council (AFRC), set up in the
wake of the May 25 coup that overthrew the civilian government,
is reported to hold a meeting today to consider the calls.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, other proposals by the four-member
cross-party mediation team include the "formation of the
broad-based government of national unity including all political
parties represented in parliament, the (rebel) Revolutionary
United Front (RUF) and other interest groups".
</P>
<P>
For this purpose, the team called for the release of Foday
Sankoh, leader of the RUF, from alleged detention in Nigeria "to
enable him to participate in the further political arrangements
of the country".
</P>
<P>
The AFRC has appointed Sankoh as its vice-chairman and
repeatedly called on Nigeria to release him.
</P>
<P>
The document issued by the team, entitled "Proposals for
Parliamentary Mediation in the Current Constitutional Crisis and
Political Stalemate in the Country", also calls for "the
guaranteed future of all officers and men involved in the
military takeover".
</P>
<P>
As for the army's bitter rivals in civil defense units, these
should be disarmed and demobilized, while all RUF fighters should
be encamped, according to the proposals.
</P>
<P>
"United Nations and ECOMOG peacekeeping force should be
stationed throughout Sierra Leone to strengthen security in the
country," the plan suggested.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, government and private sector
employees in capital Freetown continued to refuse to go back to
work, while schools, colleges, hospitals, banks and other
commercial houses remained closed.
</P>
<P>
This is "a vivid manifestation of opposition to the military
takeover," the report said, quoting Ibrahim Sorrie, secretary of
the mediation team.
</P>
<P>
"The possibility of a breakout of civil conflict among various
factions of the community continues to increase," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
