<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Human Development Index Ranking Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's ranking in the human
development index has fallen to 134 out of 175 nations this year
from 128 out of 174 countries in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 Human Development Report compiled by the United
Nations Development Program (UNDP) said that Kenya ranked 113 in
1991 in the world.
</P>
<P>
The report released by UNDP Deputy Resident Representative
Nancy Assanga on Thursday attributed Kenya's downward spiral to
the social and economic adjustment programs introduced in the
1980s, which have impoverished many people.
</P>
<P>
Cost-sharing in education and health and the liberalization
of the economy carried out by the Kenyan government had also had
adverse effects on the human development index, said John
Githongo at a reception who assisted in analyzing the data.
</P>
<P>
Recent drought and political changes have also impacted
negatively on the country's socio-economic developments, he
added.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, about 42 percent of the people in
Sub-Saharan Africa and 40 percent of that in South Asia live
below the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
Worse still, the report said, poverty is increasing in
Sub-Saharan Africa in proportion and in absolute numbers.
</P>
<P>
The HIV/Aids scourge is taking an immense toll on many
nations, leading to a reduction in life expectancy in the region,
and conflicts have also led to the decline in life expectancy in
countries like Rwanda and the Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The human development index indicates how far a country has
gone to attain certain defined goals, including an average life
expectancy, universal access to education and decent living
standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
