<HEADLINE> Pakistan Urges U.S. to Refund F-16 Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan today urged the United
States to find an amicable way out of the impasse regarding the
refund of 628 million U.S. dollars which it paid for 28 F-16
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan urges the U.S. Administration to find a solution to
the issue now that the option of refund from the F-16 aircraft
sale to Indonesia has fallen through, a Foreign Office spokesman
told a news briefing here today.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan, during his visit to
the U.S., took up the issue with State Department and other
officials, emphasizing that American must deliver the aircraft or
refund the money, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"But the U.S. Administration says that a legislation prohibits
them from the sale," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has contacted lawyers to consider the legal option
before the statute of limitation expires in 1999, he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also expressed serious concern over the reported
deployment of the Prithvi missiles by India near Pakistan's
border.
</P>
<P>
"The deployment of Prithvi missiles across our borders entails
a qualitative change in the security environment in South Asia,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"We feel that our region can ill-afford a missile race," he
said. "At the same time, we have to address our legitimate
security concerns and will take all necessary measures to meet any
threat."
</P>
<P>
"Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has addressed letters to the
leaders of the five permanent members of the U.N. Security
Council, drawing their attention to the serious degradation in the
security environment of our region," he said.
</P>
<P>
"He (Sharif) has reminded them of their special responsibility
for the preservation of international peace and security and urged
them to call upon India to excise restraint," the spokesman said.
 
</P>
