<HEADLINE> S. Africa Tries to Build Mineshaft Power Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The South Afrian power
utility Eskom is studying the possibility of using the country's
numerous disused mineshafts to generate electricity with falling
water, the local daily the Citizen reported today.
</P>
<P>
The theory is that the water, which occurs naturally at the
bottom of the mines, would be pumped to the surface then released
back down the shaft to drive a turbine generator, the report
quoted Eskom spokesman Peter Adams as saying.
</P>
<P>
The proposal held great promise becuase it could provide a
clean sources of energy, a Eskom sources said.
</P>
<P>
Dave Blake, one of the scientists working on the project, said the
research was at an early stage.
</P>
<P>
"We are doing reconnaisannce studies at the moment...We are
looking at where we could find a ite to conceptually build plant
to see how much the cost would be, to see if it is worth going
down the steps of feasibility," Blake said.
</P>
<P>
Mineshafts vary in depth from a few hundred to thousand
metres. South Africa, one of the major gold producers in the
world, has some of the deepest gold mineshafts in the world. enditem

