<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rawlings Sceptical About Coupists' Ability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings
has rebuffed an eight-man diplomatic mission from Sierra Leone's
military leader Major Johnny Koroma to discuss possible ways of
averting military action against the junta.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here today, Rawlings on
Thursday expressed doubts over the ability of the junta to
convince anybody with its diplomatic shuttles.
</P>
<P>
He told the delegation "in clear terms" to abdicate power and
restore the civilian government of President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah
ousted in the coup on May 25.
</P>
<P>
According to him, this was the only honorable path open to the
military leaders to avoid any military assault from the west
African peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
At the end of a four-hour parley with the delegation led by
former Sierra Leonean Ambassador to Germany Dauda Kamara,
Rawlings also blamed Sierra Leone's military leaders for
Tuesday's heavy exchange of gunfire between ECOMOG and
supporters of the junta.
</P>
<P>
The clash around Lungi International Airport near the capital
Freetown, according to the military regime, took place when some
of the soldiers that were dispatched to Lungi used a wrong road.
</P>
<P>
Castigating the military regime for fraternizing with the rebel
Revolutionary United Front (RUF), Rawlings was quoted as asking
the delegation "what does your government stand to gain from
associating with that kind of force that was held in low esteem
by all?"
</P>
<P>
"From all indications, your friendship with RUF is a
reflection of weakness on the part of your government," he said.
</P>
<P>
The delegation reportedly wore long faces as they departed the
venue of the meeting with Rawlings.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Koroma had asked Ghana not to join any international
force that might want to take military action against the junta.
He also sought the assistance of Rawlings to persuade other
African countries not to invade Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Koroma was reported to have warned that any international
invasion would create "serious difficulties", while pleading that
the rebels be given a chance to prove their commitment to peace
and democracy.
</P>
<P>
The RUF had been fighting a civil war in Sierra Leone since
1991 and a ceasefire was reached only in November last year when
an agreement was signed between it and Kabbah's government.
</P>
<P>
It allied to the military regime after the May 25 coup with
its former leader Foday Sankoh appointed vice-chairman of the
ruling Armed Forces Revolutionary Council.  
</P>
</TEXT>
