<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolian Foreign Trade Sees Favorable Balance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia had a favorable trade
balance of 28.3 million U.S. dollars in the first five months this
year, reversing a 6.8 million dollar trade deficit in the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics issued by the Mongolian National Statistics Bureau
show that Mongolia's foreign trade in the first five months
totalled 280.9 million dollars, of which 154.6 million were
exports and 126.3 million were imports.
</P>
<P>
The favorable trade balance resulted in a rise in the nation's
foreign exchange reserve which registered 52 million dollars this
June, a 2 million dollar increase from the registered 50 million
dollars at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia has developed its trade relations with China, Japan,
the United States, Switzerland, South Korea and Italy since the
beginning of the 1990's.
</P>
<P>
Of its total exports, 44.1 percent went to Switzerland, 21
percent to China and 8.6 percent to Russia. Of its total imports,
32.4 percent was from Russia, 13.8 percent from Italy and 10.1
from China.
</P>
<P>
Copper takes more than half of Mongolia's total export
volume. It imports crude oil from Russia and food and daily
necessities mainly from China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
