<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shelterbelts Will Help Boost Grain Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 13 (Xinhua) -- More than 2.4 million hectares of
farmland shelter-forests have been planted in the three northern
areas of China -- the northeast, north and northwest --
benefiting 21.5 million hectares of farmland, the China Forestry
News reported today.
</P>
<P>
Shelter provided by the belts could help boost grain production
in the north by 10 million tons a year, or 10 to 30 percent,
the paper estimated.
</P>
<P>
The planting of farmland shelter-forests is an important part
of China's "Three Northern Shelterbelt Project", the world's most
ambitious project to combat desertification and soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
So far 65 percent of northern farmland has been well protected
by the mass planting of trees, the paper said, adding that initial
shelterbelt systems have been established in more than 50 counties
or banners (administrative county-level regions in Inner Mongolia)
in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Surpasses Japan in Shipbuilding Orders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 13 (Xinhua) -- South Korean shipbuilding industry
outperformed its Japanese rivals in the orders received so far
this year, but underperformed in terms of value, industry sources
said today.
</P>
<P>
The orders received by South Korean shipbuilders during the
first five months reached 3.59 million tons for 58 ships, about
150,000 tons more than Japan's 3.44 million tons for 136 ships.
</P>
<P>
However, the value of the five-month orders stood at 2,722
million U.S. dollars, about 85 percent of the 3,203 million
dollars registered by Japanese shipbuilders.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that South Korean shipbuilders have obtained
orders at low prices regardless of the type of ships, while
Japanese shipbuilders selected the orders with high added values.
</P>
<P>
"South Korean shipbuilders replaced the Japanese ones to lead
in shipbuilding orders, but their management difficulties are
expected to persist due to expansion of facilities and low ship
prices," a business source said.
</P>
<P>
South Korea used to emerge as a world leader in shipbuilding
orders in 1993 with 8.32-million-ton orders, compared with Japan's
7.53 million tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
