<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minster Nawaz
Sharif will leave for Turkey Saturday to attend the first summit
of eight developing countries, a Foreign Office spokesman said
here today.
</P>
<P>
The summit -- Development-8 (D-8) -- is expected to conclude
with the formal establishment of the D-8 Group which will comprise
Turkey, Iran, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Indonesia, Malaysia, Egypt and
Nigeria, the spokesman said at a weekly news conference.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Istanbul, Turkey, Sharif will exchange views
with Turkish leaders on bilateral, regional and international
issues of mutual interest.
</P>
<P>
Sharif is also expected to have meetings with other heads of
state or government during the summit, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
After attending the D-8 summit, Sharif will pay a two-day visit
to Iran starting from June 16 on his way back from Istanbul,
according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani Prime Minister is expected to hold talks with
Iranian leaders which will "cover the entire spectrum of
Pakistan-Iran relations", the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan is desirous of close, mutually beneficial economic
ties with Iran," said the spokesman. "The visit will provide an
opportunity to review bilateral economic relations and identify
ways for further expanding and consolidating them."  
