<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Sees a Dismal Picture in Industrial Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The industrial sector in Bangladesh
is expected to achieve a growth rate of only 3.6 percent in the
current fiscal as against 5.3 percent in 1995-96 and 8.4 percent
in 1994-95, according to an official report.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 Economic Survey, released by the Finance Ministry
today, envisages that the industrial sector's contribution to GDP
(gross domestic product) would be at about 19.1 percent as against
19.5 percent the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Of the components, the manufacturing sub-sector is likely to
achieve 3.3 percent growth as against 5.3 percent in the previous
year. The growth rate was 8.6 percent in 1994-95.
</P>
<P>
The construction sub-sector envisages a growth rate of 3.6
percent, while the power, gas and water sub-sector is likely to
achieve a growth rate of 5 percent in the current fiscal.
</P>
<P>
In the manufacturing sub-sector, the medium- and large-scale
industries together are expected to record a growth rate of 3
percent in the current fiscal as against 6 percent in 1995-96. The
rate was 11.2 percent in 1994-95.
</P>
<P>
The survey report envisages a static 3.9 percent growth rate in
small and cottage industries in the current fiscal year, the same
as the previous year. The rate was 4.2 percent in 1994-95.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey report, a total of 1,218 small and
cottage industries were registered with the Bangladesh Small and
Cottage Industries Corporation (BSCIC) during the last five years
since 1991-92.
</P>
<P>
The number of entrepreneurs in small and cottage industries
also rose to 17,031 in 1995-96 from 10,920 in 1991-92.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
