<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB to Host Meeting on Assistance to the Poorest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
announced today that it will host a four-day meeting here next
week to discuss financial assistance to the poorest people in the
world.
</P>
<P>
The bank said in a statement that about 135 representatives of
donors and multilateral finance institutions will gather here from
Monday to Thursday to discuss ways to support the poorest people.
</P>
<P>
Four months ago, a micro-credit summit in Washington launched a
campaign to provide micro-credit for self-employment and other
financial and business services to 100 million of the world's
poorest families.
</P>
<P>
Next week's meeting is aimed at strengthening the ability of
micro-finance institutions to provide financial services to the
poorest, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent ADB report, about 1.3 billion people in
the world today are living in absolute poverty, or their average
income is less than one U.S. dollar a day. Of the 1.3 billion poor
people, one billion are in Asia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Denies Missiles Sale to PKK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- A Russian diplomat has said here
that Moscow has never sold missiles to the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK), local newspaper Sabah (morning) reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Russian Ambassador to Ankara Vadim Kuznetsov made the remarks
in response to the statement made by Erol Ozkasnak, Turkish
secretary general of the General Staff, at a press conference
last Friday that a Turkish Super Cobra helicopter and a Cougar
helicopter were downed in northern Iraq by Russian-made SA-7B
missiles.
</P>
<P>
Two pilots were killed when the Super Cobra helicopter was
downed at the south of Cukurca town of Haakari on May 18.
</P>
<P>
The Cougar helicopter of the Turkish armed forces was downed in
Zap region of northern Iraq on June 4, killing 11 military
personnel.
</P>
<P>
About 50,000-strong Turkish government troops, backed by air
power, have carried out cross-border military operations in
northern Iraq since May 14 in a bid to sweep the PKK rebels out
of the region.
</P>
<P>
Turkish military officials have said that at least 2,500 PKK
guerrillas have been killed in the military incursion in
northern Iraq, but the PKK claimed that its losses were less
than 100 people.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting an almost 13-year-old separatist
war for autonomy, which has claimed over 23,000 lives in eastern
and southeastern Turkey since August 1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
