<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Targets Economic Growth at 7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's economic growth in the
1997/98 fiscal year is targeted at seven percent.
</P>
<P>
According to a new budget issued by the Ugandan government
here today, the inflation rate will be 5 percent for the fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
The budget said the average rate of inflation for 1996/97 was
expected to be around 7.5 percent up from 6 percent in 1995/96.
</P>
<P>
The total domestic funded government expenditure for the year
1997/98 is budgeted at 922 billion Shillings (some 922 million
U.S. Dollars), a drop from 12.3 billion Shillings spent during
the 1996/97 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The expenditure allocations, according to the new budget,
include 52 billion Shillings for debt repayment, 29 billion
Shillings for local government elections, 31 billion Shillings
for statutory expenditure and interest payments and 37.5 billion
Shillings for universal primary education.
</P>
<P>
The budget said the domestic funding for the development
budget in 1997/98, excluding the amounts provided for the payment
of taxes on project inputs, will amount to 87.5 billion Shillings
with an additional 3 billion Shillings for net lending and
investment for parastatals.
</P>
<P>
The development budget will focus on poverty eradication, it
added.
</P>
<P>
According to the budget, there are no major tax increases
except a 20 percent increase on vehicle licene fees, while modest
reduction of about 10 percent in fuel duty has been done to check
smuggling of petrol products into the country.
</P>
<P>
Value Added Tax (VAT) of 17 percent remains almost the
same, it said, adding that maximum import duty was reduced from
30 percent to 20 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
