<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Overseas Investment to Be Liberalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 13 (Xinhua) -- South Korean companies will be free
to invest overseas as from August 1, a deregulation package
unveiled by the ministry of finance and economy said today.
</P>
<P>
Under the package, South Korean firms can invest abroad freely,
without regard to the amount of investment, by merely reporting to
their main creditor banks.
</P>
<P>
"The package is aimed at simplifying procedures for outward
direct investment and relieving the financial burden of
corporations when investing abroad," ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
Under the current regulations, companies must report to the
Central Bank of Korea if the amount of investment exceeds 10
million U.S. dollars, and if the investment abroad amounts to 50
million dollars companies must first get approval from the
government screening committee.
</P>
<P>
Despite the loosened rules, in case of projects valued at more
than 50 million dollars, companies exposed to heavy debts will
have to undergo deliberation by the screening committee, said the
officials.
</P>
<P>
As from August 1, South Korean companies will also be free from
the obligation system under which companies must raise their own
capital as part of the overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
The ministry officials said since the current overseas direct
investment has shown signs of waning, "there is no need to keep
the system intact," which has been in operation since 1995 to
regulate the rush of South Korea's outward investment.
</P>
<P>
Growth in South Korea's investment abroad amounted to 6.1
billion dollars last year on an approval basis, but the
year-to-year growth dropped to 25 percent from the 90 percent in
1994 and 37 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In return for giving full freedom to corporations in outward
investment, the ministry plans to strengthen rules on corporate
public notices on the South Korea Stock Exchange with regard to
overseas investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Calls for Wider Debts Write-Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 13 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki on Thursday called for an international
debt forgiveness program to be extended to more poor nations in
the world, the ocal daily the Citizen reported today.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki made the plea in Cape Town at the launching of a
United Nations Development Program report on poverty, urging the
world's industrialized nations to practice debt-forgiveness when
dealing with Africa.
</P>
<P>
"There has to be debt forgiveness. Some of the steps that have
been taken with regard to some of the least developed countries,
where there has been this debt forgiveness, needs to be extended
to a larger number of countries," said Mbeki, adding debt-relief
is critical for African development.
</P>
<P>
The debt forgiveness program, launched last year by the
International Monetary Fund, the World Bank and the Paris Club of
creditor nations, is aimed to write off up to 80 percent debts
for about 25 of the world's poorest countries, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has been identified as the first country to benefit,
and will have about 20 percent of its 3.5 billion US Dollars debt
forgiven in April next year.
</P>
<P>
Other probable candidates in Africa include Cote d'Ivoire,
Burkina Faso, Benin, Mali, Mozambique and Togo.
</P>
<P>
Africa has a total international debt of 340 billion US
Dollars which costs 24 billion US Dollars a year to service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
