<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China Prefecture Fighting Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Huaihua Prefecture in central
China's Hunan Province has increased economic and technological
cooperation with other areas in a bid to shake off poverty.
</P>
<P>
The prefecture, one of the nine major poverty-stricken areas in
the country, launched 186 projects involving total investment of
304 million yuan (about 36.6 million US dollars) last year in
cooperation with other parts of China.
</P>
<P>
For the first time in 1996, total output value of township
enterprises in the prefecture topped 10 billion yuan, an increase
of 73 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The prefecture, inhabited by a group of minority ethnic groups,
has been underdeveloped for years. In recent years, China has
shifted its economic development to central and western regions,
providing opportunities for Huaihua.
</P>
<P>
The prefectural government has sent a dozen group of officials
to coastal areas in southeast China to draw on management
expertise.
</P>
<P>
Twelve counties and cities in the prefecture all have
established cooperation relations with prosperous counties or
cities in coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
Through economic and technological cooperation, 23 state-owned
enterprises in Zhijiang and Jingzhou counties in the prefecture
have stepped out of financial difficulties, providing jobs for
more than 1,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The Jingjiang County Timber Mill, which was on the verge of
bankruptcy, has been revived by introducing five million yuan from
Hainan and Anhui provinces. The mill is capable of generating an
annual output value of 30 million yuan and earn 20,000 yuan in
profits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
