<HEADLINE> More Work Needed to End Stalemate: Egyptian Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian mediator Osama al-Baz
failed to persuade Israeli and Palestinian officials to return
to the negotiating table in the latest round of mediation drive
between the two sides, reported the state-run Israel Radio today.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with both Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu and Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President
Yasser Arafat Thursday, al-Baz, Egyptian presidential adviser,
told reporters that more work is needed to terminate the deadlock
in the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks that have broken off since
Israel began construction of a new settlement at Har Homa in East
Jerusalem in mid-March.
</P>
<P>
Al-Baz's meetings were to have been followed by a second
round of talks between the two negotiating teams, led by Israeli
cabinet secretary Danny Naveh and Palestinian chief negotiator
Saeb Erekat.
</P>
<P>
During their one-hour meeting in Tel Aviv, Netanyahu and
al-Baz tried to bridge the gap between Israel and the PNA over
the Har Homa construction.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side has been demanding a six-month settlement
freeze in the West Bank including East Jerusalem as a
prerequisite for convening final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
Al-Baz then proceeded to Ramallah, West Bank, for a two-hour
session with Arafat and other Palestinian officials. Palestinian
sources said that the gaps between the two sides apparently
remained as wide as ever.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian envoy, who left for home immediately afterwards,
refused to speak in terms of either pessimism or optimism
regarding the prospect of his shuttle diplomacy. However, he
said, as long as Egypt was involved in the mediation, there was
cause for hope.
</P>
<P>
Israeli diplomatic sources speculate that al-Baz is expected
to return some time next week to continue his mediation
efforts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
