<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Men Run under 10 Seconds at U.S. Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Five American sprinters, led by
Jon Drummond, ran stunningly-fast 100-meter times in preliminary
rounds at the U.S. championships in Indianapolis Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
Drummond clocked 9.92 seconds and four others run under 10
seconds in first-round races. While Marion Jones produced the
year's fastest two women's 100-meter times, dominating the
semifinals in 10.92 seconds after running 10.98 seconds in her
opening race, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Only seven men have ever run faster than Drummond, a 1996
Olympian, and no one has been faster in a non-final.
</P>
<P>
Headwinds slowed the parade of speedsters in the men's
semifinals, where three-time Olympian Dennis Mitchell was
eliminated after placing sixth in his race.
</P>
<P>
The top three finishers in the finals earn a place on the
U.S. team for the Athens world championships in August.
</P>
<P>
The shot put final was almost as impressive as the 100 meters.
</P>
<P>
World record-holder Randy Barnes decided the competition with a
put of 22.03 meters, the best in 1997. Second went to Kevin Toth
with a lifetime best of 21.78 meters and Olympian C.J. Hunter --
Marion Jones's boyfriend -- claimed third at 21.34 meters.
</P>
<P>
World champion John Godina missed a chance to defend his title,
placing fourth at 20.49 meters.
</P>
<P>
Steve Fritz, fourth in the Atlanta Olympics, won the decathlon
with 8,604 points, the second-best mark of the year, while
Olympian Kelly Blair was first in the heptathlon with a lifetime
best of 6,465 points.
</P>
<P>
The American men had not been among the year's top-five
100-meter runners until Thursday. Maurice Greene changed that with
a 9.96-second clocking in the opening heat. Only Trinidad's Ato
Boldon, at 9.89 seconds, had run faster.
</P>
<P>
Drummond came even closer to Boldon's mark with his 9.92 in the
third heat. Kareem Streete-Thompson was second at 9.96 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Also under 10 seconds were Mike Marsh, winner of the fourth
heat at 9.97 seconds, and Tim Montgomery, the fifth-heat winner at
9.96 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The wind shifted into the runners' faces before the men's
semifinals and times slowed.
</P>
<P>
Marsh ran 10.13 seconds and Drummond clocked 10.18 seconds to
pace one semifinal. Greene led the second in 10.08.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC to Speak with One Voice at CITES Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The Southern Africa Development
Community (SADC) has agreed to speak with one voice at the
ongoing 10th meeting of the Convention on International Trade in
Endangered Species (CITES) to increase winning chances of their
various proposals.
</P>
<P>
Zambia and Tanzania, which were once said to be against the
region's stance of taking a common approach at the meeting,
cleared the misconceptions at a press briefing yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The two countries announced that they will support their
fellow SADC member countries in their proposals.
</P>
<P>
The briefing, which was attended by representatives of 12 SADC
delegations, was chaired by South African high commissioner to
Zimbabwe Kingsley Mamabolo.
</P>
<P>
Director of National Parks and Wildlife Services of Zambia
Ackim Mwenya said although his country was not proposing to
downlist the African elephant, "she endorses the proposal by the
three proponent countries".
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Botswana and Namibia are proposing the downlisting
of the African elephant from Appendix I to Appendix II, which
allows restricted commercial trade in the animal's products.
</P>
<P>
A representative of the Tanzanian delegation said her country
supported the three countries, since the states had provided
enough scientific data to show reasons why they wanted their
elephants downlisted.
</P>
<P>
The SADC is also advocating for a secret ballot, if ever a
vote was to be conducted at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
However, some delegates, mainly from the west, appeared not to
listen to the problems being faced by the countries of the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Reform Trade Practices in WTO Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 13 (Xinhua) -- China, which initiated the
opening-up policy 20 years ago, has promised to further liberalize
its trade practices.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation (Moftec) reaffirmed China's commitment to reduce its
general tariff level from the current 23 to 15 percent, an average
for developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zixian in charge of policy research at Moftec made the
statement during an investment policy forum here last week.
</P>
<P>
His remarks, coinciding with China's accelerated talks on entry
into the World Trade Organization (WTO), indicated that the market
economy is still on track despite the death of Deng Xiaoping who
had transformed the country's decades-old central planned economic
system.
</P>
<P>
Although Wang, like other Chinese officials, defined China's
market economy as being socialist in nature, he was quick to say
"prevailing international economic practice is to be pursued."
</P>
<P>
Within three years of China's accession to WTO, foreign
businesses will be allowed to deal in international trade through
an automatic registration system, he explained.
</P>
<P>
The WTO has agreed that China can join as a developing member
which can remove such trade barriers as tariff and non-tariff
control gradually.
</P>
<P>
But a clear time-table for China to gain WTO membership still
has not been announced.
</P>
<P>
International companies, especially those in the Asia-Pacific
region, have demanded an early deal be made so as to promote their
profits in China.
</P>
<P>
Moftec Vice-Minister Long Yongtu has said China's 10-year long
strenuous process of applying to integrate with the world free
trade family has helped establish a market mechanism in the
Chinese economy.
</P>
<P>
Old-time convoluted government meddling has been cleared out of
businesses, Wang noted. "Trade liberalization has proven to be
effective," he concluded.
</P>
<P>
Long said last week China's current priority is to perfect a
market economy, no matter whether a time-table for WTO entry is
available or not.
</P>
<P>
A market economy, according to early British theorist Adam
Smith, is the very source of a nation's wealth, while a central
planned one usually stifles creativity.
</P>
<P>
Wang estimated China's foreign trade volume by 2010 to be
around 800 billion US dollars -- if the trading sector stays on
the right track.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
