<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Auto Industry Develops Rapidly in Czech Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Auto industry has been developing
rapidly in the Czech Republic with its output value reaching 112.9
billion koruna (about 3.74 billion U.S. dollars) last year, up
28.5 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by chairman of the Czech Automobile
Manufacturers Association Vratislav Kulhanek here today.
</P>
<P>
Kulhanek said, during the same period, the per capita output
value of auto industry increased by 18 percent to stand at 1.37
million koruna (about 44,300 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Whereas industrial development in the country has slowed down
in recent years with growth rate last year dropping to 2.4 percent
from 1995's 6.8 percent, auto industry has been on the upturn
trend.
</P>
<P>
Skoda, the biggest auto maker, produced 142,000 units during
the first four months of this year, up 21.6 percent from 1995.
</P>
<P>
As the pillar of the country's economy, export of Czech auto
industry amounted to 54 billion koruna (about 1.8 billion
dollars), accounting for 9 percent of the country's total export
volume in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
