<HEADLINE> Northwest Province to Green All Barren Hills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Shaanxi province
has decided to designate the year 1997 as the "afforestation
year", in an effort to plant trees on all the barren hills within
two years, the China Forestry News reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the province's plan, this year trees will be
planted on a total of 300,000 hectares of mountainous sides, the
paper said, adding that at present the total area of remaining
barren hills suitable for tree-planting is 520,000 hectare.
</P>
<P>
During the past years the province has made great progress in
planting trees, with many cities and counties turned all their
barren hills green,
</P>
<P>
But, the paper noted, the task of afforestation of barren
mountains is still arduous, since most of the remaining barren
hills are in the loess areas where natural conditions are harsh.
</P>
<P>
"The whole province, including six million rural households,
should be mobilized for the afforestation drive," the paper quoted
Shaanxi vice-Governor Wang Shousen as saying.
</P>
<P>
In order to make a success of this year's afforestation effort,
the province decided to allocated five million yuan (600,000 US
dollars) for tree-planting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
