<HEADLINE> Chongqing Gives Priority to Transportation (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Chongqing, a new municipality
directly under the central government following Beijing, Shanghai,
and Tianjin, will give priority to the construction of
transportation facilities in the near future.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2020, the city government is projected to invest
41.8 billion yuan (5 billion US Dollars) to build 4,680 km of
highways, including more than 950 km of superhighways, according
to its new plan.
</P>
<P>
Taking 1997 as the "Year of Road of Construction," the
government has poured a total of 2.5 billion yuan (301 million US
dollars) into this project this year, accounting for half of its
annual fiscal income.
</P>
<P>
Local transportation authorities told Xinhua that the
government plans to complete a network of highways centering on
Chongqing and covering a batch of national trunk highways and
peripheral roads, as well as a round-the-city expressway.
</P>
<P>
The Chongqing area was once described as "more difficult than
ever" in a poem by Li Bai, a famous poet in the Tang Dynasty
(618-907).
</P>
<P>
Local transportation conditions have been improved after
decades of construction since 1949. At present, more than 27,000
km of highway have gone into operation in the city.
</P>
<P>
Limited by adverse geological landscape, however, including too
many rivers, mountains, and hillocks, the city's transportation
still cannot cater to economic expansion, authorities point out.
</P>
<P>
"Chongqing's economic growth should start from transportation,"
said Pu Haiqing, the newly-elected mayor.
</P>
<P>
This is also in response to the country's strategy of shifting
the focus of economic expansion to central and western areas, and
in line with the concrete conditions of the city -- Chongqing is
too big a city, and has too large tracts of rural areas, officials
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing Gives Priority to Transportation (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Construction work has begun on an expressway from Chongqing to
Changshou, with a length of 85 km, and another super-highway from
Changshou to Fuling, totaling 54 km, and is scheduled for
completion at the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
In the latter half of this year, work will begin on an
87-km-long expressway from Chongqing to Qijiang and the
Wanxian-Liangping expressway of 67 km long, which will finish in
five and four years, respectively.
</P>
<P>
A 470-km-long Fuling-Xiushan section of the No. 319 national
highway will be upgraded by October of this year.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, five Yangtze river bridges will be built and
go into operation at Jiangjin, Fuling, Fengdu, Wanxian, and
Chongqing.
</P>
<P>
Teng Xiquan, deputy director of the municipal Communications
Bureau, said that Chongqing will have built 527 km of expressways
and 1,900 km of first- and second-grade highways by 2005.
</P>
<P>
"Our aim is to open a fast passage to the east and to the sea,
a fundamental change in Chongqing's road conditions," Teng said.
</P>
<P>
While building high-grade highways, the city will set aside 30
million yuan (3.6 million US Dollars) annually as special highway
funds, to make all towns and townships have access to highways by
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the city plans to build three new railway lines
from Chongqing to Huaihua and Suining, and from Wanxian to Daxian
by 2010, and build nine ports along the Yangtze river. Jiangbei
airport in Chongqing will be expanded, and preparations will be
done for Wuqian airport in Wanxian and Zhoubei airport in Qinjiang.
</P>
</TEXT>
