<HEADLINE> Thirteen Wounded in Albania During Election Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Thirteen people were reportedly
wounded by gun shoots on Thursday when Albanian President Sali
Berisha was addressing an election rally near this capital.
</P>
<P>
The president was not hurt in the shootouts at Elbasan, a town
about 30 kilometers southeast of Tirana, media reports said.
</P>
<P>
An Interior Ministry spokesman was quoted as saying that "five
armed men had fired in the air, then into the crowd" of thousands
of Berisha's supporters before the police responded.
</P>
<P>
But witnesses said they saw two men firing automatic weapons in
the air as the president was addressing the rally.
</P>
<P>
The two men were hurt in the subsequent shootouts along with
two police and two civilians, the witnesses said. But hospital
officials said seven people were wounded, including three
policemen and four civilians.
</P>
<P>
A separate gunfire between Berisha's bodyguards and armed
residents was reportedly to have occurred at a street corner, in
which six were wounded.
</P>
<P>
Berisha narrowly escaped an assassination attempt on June 4 at
Rushbull, 30 kilometers west of Tirana, during another campaign
function for the June 29 general elections.
</P>
<P>
More than 700 people have died and thousands injured in the
country since February this year, when the collapse of shady
investment schemes deprived many Albanians of their life savings
and triggered widespread violence.
</P>
<P>
The coming elections were designed to restore order in the
Balkan state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
