<HEADLINE> Myanmar Leader Calls for Infrastructure Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar leader Than Shwe has called
for expediting infrastructure development and eradication of
narcotics in the country's border areas.
</P>
<P>
Than Shwe, who is chairman of the Myanmar State Law and Order
Restoration Council (SLORC), made the call here Thursday at a
meeting of the Central Committee for Development of Border Areas
and National Races, the official paper The New Light of Myanmar
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Than Shwe, who is also chairman of the committee, urged
officials to give priority to construction of roads, bridges,
schools and hospitals to uplift education, health and social
standards in the areas.
</P>
<P>
The official paper also quoted SLORC First Secretary Khin Nyunt
as saying 4,768 kilometers of roads have been paved and 10,886
kilometers repaired in the past eight years since 1989 while 31
large and more than 650 small bridges and 41 dams were built.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, 35 hospitals and 338 primary
and high schools were also built mainly during the period.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the energy sector, hydropower stations were built for
areas in Shan State, northern Myanmar, bringing electricity to 120
towns and villages.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 62 television relay stations (10-100 watts), 636
kilometers of telephone trunk lines, 53 local telephone exchanges
and 41 telegraph offices were added.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar also cooperated with the U.N. Development Program and
some countries such as Japan, South Korea, Thailand and China in
implementing some development projects in border areas for
improving health, education, water supply and sanitation services
there, according to the paper.  
</P>
</TEXT>
