<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Opposition Denounce Proposed Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The opposition Bangladesh
Nationalist Party (BNP) has denounced the proposed new budget as
"anti-people" and called upon the people to build a movement
against the budget.
</P>
<P>
"It's an anti-people, anti-development and pro-Indian budget,"
BNP Secretary General Mannan Bhuiyan told an instant street
protest after Finance Minister Shah AMS Kibria Thursday night
presented to the parliament the budget for the 1997-98 fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
The budget has a total expenditure of 277.86 billion taka
(about 6.46 billion U.S. dollars) and leaves an overall deficit of
81.62 billion taka (about 1.9 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The entire economy of the country would be destroyed if this
budget is to take effect, Bhuiyan charged.
</P>
<P>
A series of new tax measures, including expansion of the
value-added tax (VAT) to retailing for some items to obtain 3.82
billion taka (about 88.8 million dollars) in additional revenue,
were proposed in the budget to take effect on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The BNP leader said this budget would lead mills, factories and
industries to destruction through encouraging smuggling from
neighboring India.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jatiya Party Chairman HM Ershad, whose party
supported the Awami League to form the government, has also
criticized the new budget and said the present government will
have to bear all its liabilities.
</P>
<P>
"We can't call it a good budget. It's not a welfare-oriented
budget," he noted in his initial reaction to the national budget,
which he said has failed to increase expenditure on the
investment-oriented sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
