<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Aims to Qualify for EMU by 1999: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Italy will push forward with its
campaign to meet the criteria for Economic and Monetary Union
(EMU) by its launch date in 1999, Italian Treasury Minister Carlo
Azeglio Ciampi said here today.
</P>
<P>
Italy is ready to adopt the euro from the start, he said at a
reception for the country's Euro Committee at the presidential
Quirinale Palace.
</P>
<P>
It would be a big mistake to start out with a "mini" euro,
limited to a small number of countries in 1999, Ciampi said, as
the success of the single currency will be measured by the number
of countries involved and by a balance between participating
northern European and Mediterranean countries.
</P>
<P>
Germany and France have been divided over whether to impose a
strict reading of the Maastricht treaty, which requires countries
joining the euro to get their public deficits to below 3
percent of Gross Domestic Product.
</P>
<P>
Ciampi said Italy is fully aware of the economic stability
required for the implementation of the single currency and is
working to improve the economy. Rome has promised a three-year
plan to cut its debt and deficit.
</P>
<P>
Italy has approached "an advanced stage" of economic
convergence, he said, "we have slashed inflation, have the
strongest balance of payments in Europe and are correcting public
accounts."
</P>
<P>
However, a forecast by the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development published today showed that Italy,
with, its deficit estimated at 3.2 percent of Gross Domestic
Product (GDP) this year and likely to rise to 3.8 percent in 1998,
will not meet the Maastricht criteria.
</P>
<P>
It said France and Germany would also have a 3.2 percent
deficit/GDP ratio this year, but would cut them to 3.0 and 2.7
percent respectively in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Ciampi said Italy's efforts to revamp its economy were not only
launched for Maastricht. "... what we do for Europe and for
correcting our accounts ... are two aspects of the same thing," he
said.
</P>
<P>
An EU meeting in April and May 1998 will decide which countries
among the 15 EU members will qualify for the single currency at
its launch in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
