<HEADLINE> Poland, Yugoslavia To Enhance Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Poland and the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia signed five agreements here today to boost bilateral
economic ties.
</P>
<P>
The accords, covering cooperation in agriculture and food, health
and medical care and double taxation avoidance, were signed by Polish
Prime Minister Wlodzimierz Cimoszewicz and visiting Yugoslav Prime
Minister Radoje Kontic.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony followed talks between the two on the
normalization and development of bilateral economic relations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Cimoszewicz described Kontic's visit as an
important event and said with international sanctions against
Yugoslavia lifted, the time for the resumption of high-level
economic cooperation and the establishment of political relations
between the two nations had come.
</P>
<P>
Poland and Yugoslavia enjoyed good economic and trade ties
before the civil war broke out in former Yugoslavia with bilateral
trade at an annual 400 million U.S. dollars. It is now down to 60
million dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
Kontic arrived here today for a two-day working visit. He is due
to meet Polish President Alexander Kwasniewski tomorrow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
