<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ahtisaari: Hong Kong's Return to China Remarkable Event </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Finnish President Martti
Ahtisaari said here today that Hong Kong's return to China on July
1 will be a remarkable event.
</P>
<P>
On his 60th birthday party held in the presidential palace this
evening, Ahtisaari told reporters he trusts the Chinese
leadership to respect Hong Kong's status after its return.
</P>
<P>
China will resume the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong on
July 1, ending Britain's 150-year rule over the region.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has promised that it will keep Hong Kong
unchanged as it is for 50 years under the policy of "one country,
two systems, Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong, a high degree
of autonomy, and prosperity and stability".
</P>
<P>
The Finnish president told Xinhua that he agreed with his
special adviser Alpo Rusi that China will develop into an economic
power in the 21st century. It's only a matter of time before China
gains the status of an economic power.
</P>
<P>
Ahtisaari said he was satisfied with the positive developments
in Finnish-Chinese relations in recent years, saying the two
countries have strengthened cooperation not only in politics and
trade, but also in legislation and other areas.
</P>
<P>
Recalling his meeting with Chinese President Jiang Zemin during
his visit to China in April, Ahtisaari said that he and Jiang
agreed that the two countries should try to double the bilateral
trade within three years.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Finland's domestic situation, the president said
Finland's economy is recovering and steadily growing at an annual
rate of 4.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
He promised the country would take steps to lower unemployment
from the present 15 percent to 10 percent or so by the end of
the century.
</P>
<P>
On international affairs, Ahtisaari said 1997 represents a
turning point in establishing a new European security structure
and Finland will continue to contribute to enhanced cooperation
and security in Europe.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that it was vital for the European Union to
remain strong and prosperous, urging it to seize the opportunity
to take in new members and optimize its foreign and security
policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
