<HEADLINE> Bulls Rodman Gets Fine and Apologizes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The NBA issued a fine of 50,000
U.S. dollars on Chicago forward Dennis Rodman Thursday for a pair
of obscene and insensitive remarks about Mormons.
</P>
<P>
The fine is the biggest in NBA history, but the league stopped
short of suspending Rodman, who will be allowed to play Friday in
Game Six of the NBA Finals against the Utah Jazz.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday in Salt Lake City, Rodman told a media gathering he
was having trouble getting his struggling game in sync because of
the "Mormons." Given an opportunity to retract the statement two
days later, he instead repeated it and offered no apology.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the fine, NBA Commissioner David Stern said that
actions that insensitive or derogatory comments involving race or
other classifications are unacceptable in the NBA. "Dennis
Rodman's comments were exactly the kind of offensive remarks that
cannot be tolerated or excused."
</P>
<P>
On Thursday morning, Rodman apologized for what he said.
</P>
<P>
"As far as religion, it's not about trying to put down
anybody's religion...I apologize for that," said Rodman.
</P>
<P>
But he was upset over the NBA fine. "They (NBA) have no reason,
no business to even get involved. Like I said, I apologize for the
religion," Rodman said.
</P>
<P>
The Bulls coach Phil Jackson also speak for his player. "To
Dennis, a Mormon may be just a nickname for people from Utah."
</P>
<P>
Rodman has been in trouble all season. The Bulls suspended him
two games in December for swearing during a live postgame
interview. In January, he drew an 11-game league ban and was fined
25,000 dollars for kicking a cameraman in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
The Bulls player, who often dressed his hair with color in
playing games, was suspended for another game for a tussle with
Milwaukee Bucks forward Joe Wolf. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
