<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Police Bust Big Drug Laboratory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian police have busted an
underground drug laboratory for the first time since the country's
independence in 1991, the press here reported today.
</P>
<P>
The laboratory, which has been hidden in two scientific
research institutions in the Donetsk and Lugansk oblasts for four
years, can produce 100 kilograms of synthetic drugs a month.
</P>
<P>
Police seized some drugs on the spot and arrested one
Belarussian and three Ukrainians. But a German suspect had fled.
</P>
<P>
While withholding the suspects' names, the police said a
Ukrainian chemist involved in the case earned 10 hryvnas (about
5.5 U.S. dollars) from every one gram of drugs he made.
</P>
<P>
The drugs were sold at an equivalent of 40 dollars per gram.
</P>
