<HEADLINE> Japan Expects to Have Its Own Space Shuttle in 2010 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Science and Technology
Agency expects to have its own space shuttle by 2010, said a
Japanese press report available here today.
</P>
<P>
Research and development costs for the shuttle, capable of
shuttling cargo between Earth and orbit, will be included in the
fiscal 1998 budget, the report quoted officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
By replacing the current signal-use rockets with the shuttle,
the report said, Japan's launch-related expenditures will be cut
by 8.5 billion yen (about 74 million U.S. dollars) per mission.
</P>
<P>
Regular space missions are likely in the next century for
building an international space station and inevitable maintenance
calls for orbiting communications satellites, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's shuttle will be used in transporting personnel and
materials for such missions, it said.
</P>
<P>
To cut the cost, the shuttle is expected to be powered by
Japanese-made rocket engines based on the U.S.-made HZA rocket.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0213 </DOCNO>
