<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Opposes Foreign Interference, President Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav President Zoran Lilic
said today that his country opposes outside interference in its
own affairs on the pretext of human rights and the issue of
minorities, the Tanjug news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The country had become a target for foreign political pressure,
the news agency quoted the president as saying in a speech at a
military school.
</P>
<P>
Certain foreign forces, taking advantage of issues of human
rights and the rights of minorities in Kosovo, southern
Serbia, had exerted political pressure on the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
So far as Kosovo was concerned, the problem was not one of
expanding autonomy there, but of some Albanian nationalists in the
region not recognizing the country's constitution, he said.
</P>
<P>
These people, trying every means to internationalize the issue,
wanted to set up an independent "republic of Kosovo," and then
might integrate it into some other country, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo, an autonomous province of over 10,000 square kilometers
in southern Serbia, one of Yugoslavia's two republics, is home to
some 2 million people, 90 percent of whom are ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Some Albanians there have long wanted to set up an independent
state of their own in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
