<HEADLINE> Nepali MP Refuses to Join Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Just a day after Prakash Chandra
Lohani resigned as the Nepali foreign minister, another member
from his party turned down the portfolio offered him in the
cabinet reshuffle following Lohani's resignation.
</P>
<P>
MP Mahendra Raya, who was given the portfolio of state minister
for land reforms and management, said Thursday evening that he had
refused to join the ruling coalition led by Prime Minister
Lokendra Bahadur Chand, who is from his own National Democratic
Party (RPP), The Kathmandu Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
Raya told a press briefing held at Lohani's residence that he
met Chand Thursday morning following the announcement of his
appointment, but he rejected the offer despite pressures from the
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Raya said he had written to the prime minister expressing his
aversion to take up the post offered to him "since I feel it is
not proper to carry on the coalition with the UML in the present
context."
</P>
<P>
He also criticized the growing size of the cabinet, saying it
was against the government's avowed policy of sleek governance.
</P>
<P>
Besides Lohani and Raya, three other RPP lawmakers were also
present at the press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Lohani, who resigned as foreign minister Wednesday in protest
against alleged widespread irregularities in the local elections,
said at the press briefing that the coalition in the present
political context is unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Chand appointed a new foreign minister from his
cabinet and expanded it by inducting three RPP MPs including Raya.
</P>
<P>
Lohani said he has not pressured any of his colleagues in the
government to resign, but is confident that they would take their
decision according to their conscience.
</P>
<P>
"The individual efforts of party members have to be transformed
into a collective effort," he added.
</P>
<P>
Chand formed the present government with the participation of
the CPN-UML in March when he managed to topple the former
coalition by withdrawing his RPP party from it.  
</P>
</TEXT>
