<HEADLINE> Elephants Destroy Crop in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 13 (Xinhua) -- About 70 wild elephants destroyed
crops worth more than 20 million baht (800,000 U.S. dollars)
Thursday in eight villages in Phetchaburi Province, western
Thailand, according to a report today.
</P>
<P>
The destroyed crops include bananas, corn and pineapples on
almost 200 rai (32 hectares) of land.
</P>
<P>
The raid has led to the bankruptcy of many planters, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
"There were about 40-50 elephants eating crops in my fields,"
Saifon Muangkram, a pineapple planter, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Now I don't know what to do for a living because I have no
money left. The cost for those lost pineapples was no less than
800,000 baht (32,000 dollars)," he said.  
</P>
