<HEADLINE> U.S. Congress Passes Disaster Aid Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Congress today passed
an 8.6-billion-U.S. dollar disaster aid bill after stripping it of
provisions that sparked a veto by President Clinton earlier this
week.
</P>
<P>
The bill was approved by a vote of 78-21 in the Senate and
348-74 in the House, paving the way for President Clinton to sign
it into law soon.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, Clinton said he applauded Congress for
approving a compromise disaster relief bill that will pump money
into states racked by natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he was "especially pleased" the Republican
majority in Congress "heeded the call of common sense" by passing
a bill that did not include two unrelated riders.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, 5.6 billion U.S. dollars will be provided for
emergency relief for victims of disasters in 35 states, and 1.9
billion dollars to support a Bosnia peacekeeping mission and
maintain a no-fly zone over Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Two controversial provisions that Republicans inserted into the
vetoed bill were dropped from the replacement measure.
</P>
<P>
One was designed to prevent a government shutdown this fall and
the other was a proposal to ban sampling in the next U.S. census.
</P>
</TEXT>
