<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Blood Bank Sees Tight Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's national blood bank is
facing a serious shortage of blood, which has significantly
affected medical services for people around the country, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's National Blood Center collects 25,000 to 28,000
units of blood each month, but hospitals nationwide require 30,000
to 33,000 units monthly for their patients, Chaivej Nujproyoon,
head of the blood bank, said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The center can supply only 700 to 800 units of blood a day,
while daily demand from hospitals is at least 1,000 units,
Chaivej was quoted today as saying by local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Lack of blood supply often causes delay of surgery operations
on patients, he added.
</P>
<P>
About 70 percent of the blood from the center is used for
surgery and the rest for patients who need blood transfusions as
part of their treatment, according to the official.  
</P>
</TEXT>
