<HEADLINE> Clinton Signs Revised Disaster Aid Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
tonight signed a revised 8.6-billion-dollar disaster aid bill soon
after the Republican-controlled Congress had passed it.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Senate voted 78-21 and the House approved the bill
by a vote of 348-74 after stripping out two provisions that
sparked the president's veto earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, Clinton said he applauded Congress for
approving a compromise disaster relief bill that will pump money
into states racked by natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
"When our people are in need, we Americans come to their
assistance as one nation," Clinton said. "I applaud Congress for
heeding my call to remember that fundamental principle."
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, 5.6 billion dollars will be provided for
emergency relief for victims of disasters in 35 states, and 1.9
billion dollars to support a Bosnia peacekeeping mission and
maintain a no-fly zone over Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Two controversial items that Republicans inserted into the
vetoed bill were dropped from the replacement measure.
</P>
<P>
One was designed to prevent a government shutdown this fall,
although at funding levels that Democrats said would have caused
deep cuts in social spending.
</P>
<P>
The anti-shutdown issue will be debated in separate legislation.
</P>
<P>
The other was a proposal to ban sampling in the nation's next
census and it was replaced with a government study of methods the
Census Bureau intends to use to apply statistical adjustments of
an expected undercount of the population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
