<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Memory Drug Offers Hope to Alzheimer's Sufferers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- American scientists have shown how
a drug can improve working memory, the part of a human being's
memory used to temporarily hold information, the Daily Telegraph
reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The study, the first to use a brain scanner on the
memory-enhancing drug physostigmine, gives hope to those who
suffer from Alzheimer's disease and patients with other memory
problems.
</P>
<P>
Dr Maura Furey, lead scientist of the study carried out by
the National Institute on Ageing in Bethesda, Maryland, in the
United States, said that volunteers given the drug were better at
recognizing faces they had seen.
</P>
<P>
She suggested that since physostigmine improved the brain's
response to memory tasks, similar drugs enhancing the so-called
"cholinergic system" might help Alzheimer's sufferers.
</P>
<P>
The drug might enhance efficiency by focusing on the task at
hand, or it could help minimize the effects of distracting
stimuli.
</P>
<P>
Either way, a more efficient working memory could be a great
help to those with Alzheimer's disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Panel Passes Bill on Paying U.N. Dues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate Foreign
Relations Committee today passed a bill clearing the way for
payment of U.S. arrears to the United Nations, but with
substantial conditions attached.
</P>
<P>
The bill, approved by a vote of 14-4, was described by
Democrats and Republicans as the best possible arrangement
hammered out during four months of detailed bipartisan
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, the U.S. will pay the United Nations 819
million U.S. dollars in back dues. But in return, the world body
must cut spending and staff and reduce Washington's annual dues.
</P>
<P>
The bill said that the United States would pay the debt only
when the United Nations agrees to reduce the U.S.'s contribution
to its regular budget from 25 percent to 20 percent within three
years, and its share of the peacekeeping budget from 31 to 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
The United States has been sharply criticized by other
U.N. members, including its allies, for not paying its U.N. dues in
time.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations says the United States owes it some
1.4 billion dollars, but Sen. Jesse Helms, chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, insists that the figure is 819
million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
