<HEADLINE> High Rate of School Failures in Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The failure rate among state
school students in Panama rose considerably between 1990 and 1996,
according to an investigation by a Panamanian newspaper published
today.
</P>
<P>
Students who failed at secondary and primary school levels
showed serious deficiencies in mathematics, sciences, geography,
Spanish, and English, the study said.
</P>
<P>
The failure rate of the 335,746 students registered in
primary schools was 8 percent, with failure rates among 165,062
secondary school students was 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
First-graders at the primary level registered the highest rate
of failures last year, followed by second- and third-graders.
</P>
<P>
The subjects that saw the highest number of failures at the
primary level between 1990 and 1997 were Spanish, mathematics,
natural sciences, and social studies, while at the secondary
level, mathematics, Spanish, and sciences showed the highest
failures.
</P>
<P>
Panama has 3,683 state schools with 18,956 classrooms and
28,749 teachers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
