<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peruvian Expert Warns Authorities of "El Nino" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- A Peruvian meteorology expert has
warned of the potential damage to the country from the
increasingly frequent occurrence of the weather phenomenon known
as El Nino, characterized by heavy rain and storms.
</P>
<P>
He has called on the government to strengthen and reinforce
river bridges so that they can resist the substantial increases in
the volume of water currents El Nino could bring.
</P>
<P>
Ena Jaimes Espinosa, director of Climatology at the National
Meteorology and Hydrology (Senamhi) was quoted in the media today
as saying authorities must take into account the increasing
frequency of El Nino to anticipate potential problems caused by
changes in weather patterns.
</P>
<P>
El Nino's frequency has increased from once every eight years
to once every four years, Espinosa said. It is caused by
extraordinary water currents initiated from the eastern part of
the Pacific Ocean and typically causes temperatures in the Pacific
Ocean off the coast of Peru to rise one to two, or sometimes two
to five degrees higher than normal.
</P>
<P>
The phenomenon generally appears around Christmas time, but its
latest appearance started in the autumn, Espinosa said.
</P>
<P>
This change implies that the consequences cannot be anticipated
yet.
</P>
<P>
"The phenomenon is in its initial phase in our country. The
establishment and development stages are yet to come. However, it
is difficult to say what can happen," Espinosa said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
