<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traditional Mongolian Medicine Thrives in Inner Mongolia (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, June 13 (Xinhua) -- As part of the effort to develop
traditional Chinese medicine, the government has stressed research
on ancient Mongolian medicine and made it boom over the past 50
years.
</P>
<P>
The Mongolian ethnic group is one of China's 55 national
minorities. The majority of its people live in the Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region in north China. With its unique theoretical
system and diagnostic methods, Mongolian medicine is a key
component of China's traditional herbal medicine.
</P>
<P>
With a history of 2,000 years, Mongolian medicine is also a
major part of the Mongolians' outstanding culture.
</P>
<P>
"Mongolian medicine has its unique advantages in treating
chronic and difficult diseases, such as stomach trouble, liver and
gall disorder, coronary heart disease, gynecological disease, and
problems related to blood, skin and bone," said Uliji Tugus,
vice-president of the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region's Hospital
for Chinese and Mongolian Medicine.
</P>
<P>
The senior specialist in Mongolian medicine said clinical
research on this type of medicine has made considerable progress
in recent years. The treatment of hemiparalysis caused by
cerebrovascular accident, a method developed by doctors at the
hospital, was awarded by the Ministry of Health as a major
scientific achievement.
</P>
<P>
And the doctors have also developed therapies for blood
platelet-related disease, anemia, hepatitis B, impotence and
rheumatoid arthritis.
</P>
<P>
In traditional Mongolian medicine, five magic therapies--
acupuncture, moxibustion, medicinal bathing, massage and blood
letting-- had been widely used but were nearly lost in modern
times.
</P>
<P>
Ulan, a 34-year-old woman doctor with the hospital, has
retrieved the lost therapies through painstaking research over
eight years. Her achievement in relieving the pain of patients has
won approval from her counterparts both in China and around the
world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traditional Mongolian Medicine Thrives in Inner Mongolia (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An injured Japanese sportsman, at the suggestion of the World
Health Organization (WHO), came to the hospital in 1991, when he
was unable to walk or remember things. After being treated for one
and a half months, he resumed his memory and was able to walk
again.
</P>
<P>
A patient from the People's Republic of Mongolia, who had
suffered from a knee joint spur, had to undergo amputation
according to the diagnosis of foreign doctors.
</P>
<P>
Reluctant to receive such a surgical operation, he came here
and was treated in Mongolian medicine for two and a half months,
he saved his leg which had improved greatly.
</P>
<P>
Uliji said that recommended by WHO since 1990, the hospital has
received dozens of overseas patients who suffered from chronic
rheumatoid arthritis, cerebral hemorrhage and bed-wetting, and the
treatment proved effective and satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1958, the hospital is located in the central
part of Hohhot, capital city of Inner Mongolia, as a center for
traditional Chinese and Mongolian medicine, and medical research
and training.
</P>
<P>
Since the founding of the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region 50
years ago, it has established 45 institutions related to Mongolian
medicine, including six research institutes, one medical college
and four secondary schools with more than 3,800 professionals in
Mongolian medicine.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 50 years, medical workers have collected more
than 550 classical works in Mongolian medicine and published some
50 medical works. Medical workers have also presented over 1,000
academic papers in China and overseas. In addition, they have
collected 1,200 traditional prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
In the past decade, medical scholars from Mongolia, the
Commonwealth of Independent States, Poland, Hungary, Japan, the
Republic of Korea, the United States and Britain have come here to
study Mongolian medicine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
