<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Gets Education Loans from BID </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American Development
Bank (BID) has approved a loan of 58.1 million U.S. dollars to Panama
to modernize the country's education system, the Education
Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
The 25-year loan, supplemented by additional government funding
of 15.2 million dollars, will support a six-year program to
improve teacher training, evaluation and management systems and
upgrade teaching equipment, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The program is expected to raise the percentage of students
finishing sixth grade from the current 78 percent to 90 percent by
2000.
</P>
<P>
The loan will have a six year grace period and carry a variable
interest rate, which is now 6.9 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank will also give Panama 38 million dollars to
complement the education modernization project.
</P>
<P>
The Panamanian government has already provided 879.7 million
dollars of loans for education projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
