<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast China Province to Green All Mountains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning Province in northeast
China plans to bring greenery to all its mountains by the end of
1998.
</P>
<P>
The province's forest area has increased from 2.8 million
hactares in 1949 to the present 4.67 million hectares over the
past four decades and more, with a forest reserve volume of 180
million cubic meters. But there are still 700,000 hectares of
barren hills in the province.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Guangdong Province in south China made all its
barren hills green seven years ago, becoming the first province in
China to eliminate barren hills. The number of such provinces as
Guangdong rose to 13 two years ago.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Forestry set forth a goal of having additional
nine such provinces by the end of the century, which will include
Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
Most of the barren hills in Liaoning are located in
economically-backward counties and regions, with adverse natural
conditions and low precipitation.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has decided to increase bonuses to
those counties and regions for fulfilling the task of planting
trees on barren hills, and financial input in the afforestation
drive at all government levels.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, various kinds of preferences, including those for
share holding system, contract signing, and drawing foreign
investment, have been worked out by the provincial government to
encourage more people to participate in the drive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
