catapulted up from 66 by his French victory, downed another
Spaniard Jacobo Diaz 6-4, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year old Brazilian, who is seeded eighth here, also
clocked up his 14th consecutive victory.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Italian Andrea Gaudenzi battled for two hours and 20
minutes for his place in the quarter finals.
</P>
<P>
Argentinian Franco Squillari conceded the match only on the
16th point of a tie-break in the third set after taking the first
set 6-4 but losing the second 4-6.
</P>
<P>
In another Spain-Brazil duel, second seeded Felix Mantilla used
three sets to edge Fernando Meligeni 6-7, 7-5, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Mantilla now faces Ecuador's Nicolas Lapentti while Gaudenzi
takes on six seed Karim Alami of Morocco. Fellow Moroccan Hicham
Arazi, seeded five, will play Italian Marzio Martelli.  
