<HEADLINE> China to Speed Up Express Service Mail to Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 13 (Xinhua) -- China Post under the Ministry of
Posts and Telecommunications will speed up express mail service
(EMS) deliveries between major Chinese cities and Hong Kong this
month, today's China Daily quoted a China Post official as saying.
</P>
<P>
From June 16 to August 15, express mail will be delivered to
customers on the following day between eight mainland cities and
Hong Kong, said Xu Kuai, deputy director of China Post.
</P>
<P>
The cities are Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, Shenzhen, Nanjing,
Hangzhou, Xiamen and Shantou. And express mail from Tianjin,
Zhuhai, Suzhou, and Wuxi can also arrive in Hong Kong the next day.
</P>
<P>
EMS deliveries rely heavily on aircraft, Xu said, adding that
China Post has gained the support from and cooperation with the Civil
Aviation Administration of China(CAAC), and customs departments.
</P>
<P>
China Post will give a 30 percent discount to EMS deliveries
whose destination is Hong Kong during this period, to mark the
forthcoming return of Kong Kong to the motherland on July 1, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The move is also aimed at competing for a bigger EMS market
with foreign-funded EMS companies operating in China, which have
an upper hand in the Chinese market, forcing China Post's market
share to gradually decrease.
</P>
<P>
China Post began to provide express mail service 17 years ago,
and has set up EMS links with more than 200 countries and
regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
