<HEADLINE> Colombia: More Private Investments in Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Private investments in
infrastructure in Colombia had an annual increase of 31.3 percent
last year, the National Economic and Social Policies Council said.
</P>
<P>
The capital input reached an equivalent of 2.2 billion
U.S. dollars in 1996, said the council, known as the Conpes in
Spanish, in a report published here today by the press.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, investments in mines and energy amounted to 1.8
billion dollars, a 40 percent growth; and those in transportation
added up to 140 million dollars, a 43.5 percent rise.
</P>
<P>
If last year's quick increase against the previous year
continues into the future, the Conpes said, private investments
will rise during the 1995-1998 period to 8 billion dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
