<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> City Vows to Become Southwest Powerhouse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 13 (Xinhua) -- The inland, underdeveloped city of
Liupanshui will take advantage of its natural resources, open
itself to the outside world in a major effort to turn over a new
leaf, and become Southwest China's energy powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
Guan Yanhe, secretary of the committee of the Chineses
Communist Party of Liupanshui, told China Daily that other cities
are advancing with giant strides while Liupanshui has lagged far
behind.
</P>
<P>
"We must not procrastinate until the situation turns worse,"
Guan said.
</P>
<P>
The city is rich in natural resources with over 30 kinds of
minerals from coal, iron, lead, zinc, copper, silver, gold,
limestone, dolomite and barite to iceland spar.
</P>
<P>
Its large reserves of high-quality, easy-to-mine coal won
Liupanshui the titles of "coal metropolis of the south" and "the
black pearl."
</P>
<P>
But burdened with sluggish enterprises, insufficient
infrastructure and lack of capital, Liupanshui, with a population
of 2.6 million consisting of 38 nationalities living in 9,914
square meters, trails far behind China's booming coastal cities.
</P>
<P>
Guan noted that the opportunity is here. Under the Ninth
Five-year Plan (1996-2000), the State Council, together with other
State ministries and Guizhou province, plans to build Liupanshui
into a super-scale mineral development area and a center of
coal-derived electricity, coal chemistry, iron and steel, building
materials and aluminium.
</P>
<P>
Mayor Yi Shengjin said the city's development plan and strategy
set the target of the city's gross domestic product at 4.8 billion
yuan (578 million US dollars) by 2000, compared with 2.9 billion
yuan in 1995.
</P>
<P>
To accomplish that, the city must achieve an average yearly
growth rate of 10.5 percent from 1996 to 2000. And for its GDP to
reach the expected 13.6 billion yuan by 2010, an average annual
growth rate of 11 percent curing the 2000-2010 period will be
called for.
</P>
<P>
To secure those goals, Mayor Yi said the city government will
carry out the opening of the city with a series of preferential
polities not only to attract investment, but to introduce
technology and bring in capable personnel from home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the city mayor described Liupanshui as a virgin place
for overseas investment and also a place full of fortune and
opportunity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Launches Government Management Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 13 (Xinhua) -- A computer network aimed at
raising the efficiency of the city's government administrative
departments and improving social services has been launched in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Named as the "golden network", the large-scale computer
information management system links up the capital city's
departments of industry and commerce at various
levels. Benefitting from the network are the department at the
city government as well as 18 of its bureaus at district and
county level and their 200 agencies at grass-roots level.
</P>
