<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Old Movies a Hit in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 13 (Xinhua) -- Nostalgia is mixing with the
spirit of celebration here among townspeople who are expressing
their feelings for the return of Hong Kong by watching old Hong
Kong movies.
</P>
<P>
Recently, downtown cinemas kicked off a retrospective show of
Hong Kong films shot over the past four decades. Box office sales
topped those of new releases, and ticket sellers report that
phones are ringing non-stop from callers wanting show times.
</P>
<P>
Some hard-core fans can recall their experience 10 or 20 years
ago when they stood in line overnight for a ticket to see movies
such as "Three Smiles," a romantic comedy about an ancient scholar
and a pretty housemaid. The movie is remembered especially for
breathing fresh air into Chinese cinemas in the aftermath of the
Cultural Revolution.
</P>
<P>
"Black market prices used to deter me in those days," said
movie-goer Mao Juan. "Now I've got a chance to see these movies,
and I won't let it go."
</P>
<P>
She's not alone: a man in his 40s braved a two-hour bus ride
from the outskirts of town just to catch a morning movie. And one
young man who was low on cash left his pager at the ticket office as
collateral for a ticket, and came back for it the next day. Many
women have called the cinemas urging that each movie be shown more
than once -- in case they miss the first viewing.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai cinemas have responded well to their customers, adding
additional movie showings, and bringing to town 14 more old Hong
Kong movies from nearby Jiangsu and Zhejiang provinces and also
Beijing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
