<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Asks Business Leaders Help for China's MFN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton today
asked U.S. business leaders to convince Congress of the necessity
to extend the Most Favored Nation (MFN) trade status to China for
the coming year.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the Business Round Table, an association of
business executives, Clinton said, "What... I hope you will say to
members of Congress in both parties is that this (MFN status)
is... about what is in the interest of the American people and
what is most likely to give us the largest amount of influence and
cooperation with China in the years ahead."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said every president since 1980 has extended MFN to
China. "Ending that would end our strategic dialogue," he added.
</P>
<P>
He also said MFN is the most wrongly worded term in government
language, and the United States just simply seeks to continue the
status quo, treating China as "we do" other normal trading
partners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
