<HEADLINE> US, Uzbekistan to Create Joint Commission for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. and Uzbekistan have
agreed to create a joint commission for deeper relations following
a series of discussions completed here, the U.S. State Department
announced today.
</P>
<P>
The joint commission will be inaugurated in the autumn of 1997,
said State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns.
</P>
<P>
"This joint commission is intended to push forward all aspects
of our bilateral relationship, including political cooperation,
military, trade and investment, and energy cooperation," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott may chair
the future commission.
</P>
<P>
"This is a sign that we do want to improve our relationship
with Uzbekistan," he said. "We have a promising relationship with
Uzbekistan."
</P>
<P>
Uzbekistan is a "very important country" for the U.S. in both
geopolitical and commercial terms, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"We do want to improve our relationship. We have been working
on this for a long time," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
