<HEADLINE> Canada Still Best Place to Live: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 12 (Xinhua) -- Canada is still the best place to
live, according to this year's United Nations Human Development
Report officially released today.
</P>
<P>
For the fourth time in a row, Canada has claimed the top spot
on the UN Development Program's human-development index, which
measures life expectancy, literacy and income.
</P>
<P>
France, Norway and the United States came next in line.
</P>
<P>
Canada also scored first on a separate gender-related index,
which measures the status of women. That was an improvement from
last year's second-place showing.
</P>
<P>
"This year's report shows that Canada not only remains the best
country in the world, but that we continue to improve our living
standards," Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien said in a
statement today.
</P>
<P>
"I am also very pleased that Canada ranked number one on the
gender-related development index. We will work hard to maintain
this position and to advance in other areas, especially youth
employment," Chretien said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the confidence that new jobs and improved economic
conditions would come with the progress in restructuring public
finances.
</P>
<P>
"Canada's position in the world, as ranked in this report, is a
feather in our cap," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"But it also means that we have a great responsibility, not
only to all Canadians, but to the less fortunate in developing
countries," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
