<HEADLINE> US Dollar Surges Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar ended a weeklong
decline today with the biggest one-day jump against the yen in
nearly two years after Japan's top foreign-exchange policymaker
said the Japanese currency was too strong.
</P>
<P>
Traders who had bet on further dollar drops turned to buy the
dollar instead as it rose on the comments by Eisuke Sakakibara,
director of the Finance Ministry's international finance bureau,
early in the trading day.
</P>
<P>
The dollar touched an intraday high of 115.70 yen before
settling in New York at 114.25 yen, up 3.05 yen or 2.7 percent
from 111.20 yen Wednesday. It was the biggest one-day rise in the
dollar against the yen since a 4.15-yen advance on August 15,
1995, and erased much of the U.S. currency's retreat over the past
week.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also cost 1.7300 marks, up from 1.7160 Wednesday and
the highest level since May 5. The pound cost 1.6316 U.S. dollars,
down from 1.6377 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other late-dollar rates in New York compared with late
Wednesday: 1.4436 Swiss francs, up from 1.4375; 5.8360 French
francs, up from 5.0835; 1,698.85 Italian lire, up from 1,694.50;
1.3842 Canadian dollars, down from 1.3873. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Congress Cannot Legislate for UN: Annan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 12 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said here today that the United States Congress could not
legislate for the other 184 U.N. members, who might not accept its
conditions for paying back dues.
</P>
<P>
Referring to a bill on paying 819 million dollars of U.S.
arrears with a number of conditions, Annan told a news conference,
"One can discuss these things in Congress. It does not mean that
it is going to become law in the U.N. It does not necessarily mean
that the member states are going to accept it."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. owes the world organization 1.3 billion dollars,
accounting for more than half of the total outstanding
contributions.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.S. would have to come and negotiate and
discuss with the other member states. It was going to be quite a
challenge for U.S. diplomacy, he added.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the U.S. government realized this. He did not think
that Congress could take decisions and impose them unilaterally on
the other 184 member states.
</P>
<P>
As a condition of the U.S. payment, the bill before the
Republican-dominated Congress would demand a string of U.N.
spending cuts, a reduction in U.S. annual dues and other
concessions.
</P>
<P>
As the legislation was still being negotiated between the U.S.
government and Congress, Annan said he was very pleased with a
speech by Senator Richard Lugar, a leading Republican senator, who
pressed for U.S. fulfillment of its obligations.
</P>
<P>
Annan said, "The president himself is convinced that the U.N.
is essential for the United States, just as we need the U.S. to
participate actively in this organization. He also believes that
if the United States is going to lead and play an effective role
in this organization, it has to pay its way."
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general said he was briefed by Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and the State Department last week on the very
tough and delicate negotiations between the government and
Congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
