<DOCNO> XIE19970613.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Sails Past 7,700 Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 12 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks rocked to record
highs for the fifth consecutive session today, as a weak May
retail sales report erased any worries or fear that the Federal
Reserve would soon raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average pushed through 7,600 easily
and then sailed past 7,700 to close at 7,711.47.
</P>
<P>
The Dow jumped 135.64 points for the whole session. The
blue-chip gauge is up over 20 percent from its intraday low on
April 14.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 592.73 million
shares as against 513.74 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 13.19 to 882.76, and
the NYSE's composite index rose 7.14 to 460.64, both setting
their fifth consecutive record highs.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index gained 3.48 to 1,411.33. The
American Stock Exchange composite rose 3.45 to 626.12, the fourth
in a run.
</P>
<P>
Stocks opened higher along with bond prices, after the Commerce
Department said retail sales fell for a third straight month in
May, slipping another 0.1 percent, following declines of 0.9
percent in April and 0.3 percent in March. Economists expected a
gain of 0.3 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
The 30-year Treasury bond was up 1 point, pushing its yield
down to 6.76 percent from 6.84 late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The stock market also benefited from a report that net cash
flows into equity funds rose 18 percent in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
